# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-fribourg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] An **academic degree** is a qualification awarded to a student upon successful completion of a course of study in higher education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Academic degrees are commonly structured in levels, most often categorized as undergraduate and postgraduate degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The most common undergraduate qualification is the bachelor's degree, although some educational systems also offer lower-level degrees such as the associate degree or the foundation degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Postgraduate degrees include the engineer's degree, the master's degree, and the doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In the UK and countries whose educational systems are based on the British system, honours degrees are divided into classes: first, second (broken into upper second, or 2.1, and lower second, or 2.2) and third class.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doceo*, "I teach") first appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach (Latin: *licentia docendi*) at a medieval university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church when the term "doctor" referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* was originally reserved by the church which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed the access – now largely free of charge – of all able applicants, who were, however, still tested for aptitude by the ecclesiastic scholastic.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] This right remained a point of contention between the church authorities and the slowly emancipating universities, but was granted by the Pope to the University of Paris in 1231 where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] While the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*Baccalaureus*), it was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the Magister and doctorate, both of which now became the exclusive qualification for teaching.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In universities, doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Master of Arts" was seven years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] This was the same as the term of apprenticeship for other occupations.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Today the terms "master" (from the Latin *magister*, lit.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] 'teacher'), "Doctor", and "Professor" signify different levels of academic achievement, but in the Medieval university, they were equivalent terms.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The use of them in the degree name was a matter of custom at a university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Most universities conferred the Master of Arts, although the highest degree was often termed Master of Theology/Divinity or Doctor of Theology/Divinity, depending on the place.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The earliest doctoral degrees (theology – *Divinitatis* Doctor (D.D.), law – *Legum* Doctor (LL.D., later D.C.L.) and medicine – *Medicinæ* Doctor (M.D., D.M.)) reflected the historical separation of all higher university study into these three fields.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Over time, the D.D. has gradually become less common outside theology and is now mostly used for honorary degrees, with the title "Doctor of Theology" being used more often for earned degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Studies outside theology, law, and medicine were then called "philosophy", due to the Renaissance conviction that real knowledge could be derived from empirical observation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The degree title of Doctor of Philosophy is a much later creation and was not introduced in England before 1900.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Studies in what once was called philosophy are now classified as sciences and humanities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in medieval Islamic madrasas in the 9th century was the origin of the doctorate that later appeared in medieval European universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Alfred Guillaume, Syed Farid al-Attas and Devin J.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Stewart agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the university degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Stewart finds that the *ijazat al-ifta*, license to teach Islamic law and issue legal opinions, is most similar to the medieval European university degree in that it permits entry into certain professions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] A key difference was that the granting authority of the *ijaza* was an individual professor whereas the university degree was granted by a corporate entity.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The University of Bologna in Italy, regarded as the oldest university in Europe, was the first institution to confer the degree of Doctor in Civil Law in the late 12th century; it also conferred similar degrees in other subjects, including medicine.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The University of Paris used the term "master" for its graduates, a practice adopted by the English universities of Oxford and Cambridge, as well as the ancient Scottish universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The term "bachelor" comes from the Latin *baccalaureus*, a term previously used to describe a squire (i.e., apprentice) to a knight.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Further study and, in particular, successful participation in, and moderation of, disputations would earn one the Master of Arts degree, from the Latin magister, "master" (typically indicating a teacher), entitling one to teach these subjects.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Masters of Arts were eligible to enter study under the "higher faculties" of Law, Medicine or Theology and earn first a bachelor's and then master's or doctor's degree in these subjects.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Thus, a degree was only a step on the way to becoming a fully qualified master – hence the English word "graduate", which is based on the Latin *gradus* ("step").
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The naming of degrees eventually became linked to the subjects studied.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Scholars in the faculties of arts or grammar became known as "masters", but those in theology, medicine and law were known as "doctors".
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] As a study in the arts or grammar was a necessary prerequisite to study in subjects such as theology, medicine and law, the degree of doctor assumed a higher status than the master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] This led to the modern hierarchy in which the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), which in its present form as a degree based on research and dissertation is a development from 18th- and 19th-century German universities, is a more advanced degree than the Master of Arts (M.A.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The practice of using the term *doctor* for PhDs developed within German universities and spread across the academic world.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The French terminology is tied closely to the original meanings of the terms.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] "bachelor") is conferred upon French students who have completed their secondary education and allows the student to attend university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] When students graduate from university, they are awarded a *licence*, much as the medieval teaching guilds would have done, and they are qualified to teach in secondary schools or proceed to higher-level studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Spain had a similar structure: the term *"Bachiller"* was used for those who finished the secondary or high-school level education, known as *"Bachillerato"*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The standard Spanish university 5-year degree was *"Licenciado"*, (although there were a few 3-year associate degrees called *"diplomaturas"*, from where the *"diplomados"* could move to study a related *licenciatura*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In the past, degrees have been directly issued by the authority of the monarch or by a bishop, rather than any educational institution.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In Great Britain, Lambeth degrees are still awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The Archbishop of Canterbury's right to grant degrees is derived from the Peter's Pence Act 1533, which empowered the Archbishop to grant dispensations previously granted by the Pope.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Among educational institutions, St David's College, Lampeter, was granted limited degree awarding powers by royal charter in the nineteenth century, despite not being a university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The University College of North Staffordshire was also granted degree awarding powers on its foundation in 1949, despite not becoming a university (as the University of Keele) until 1962.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Following the Education Reform Act 1988, many educational institutions other than universities have been granted degree-awarding powers, including higher education colleges and colleges of the University of London, many of which are now effectively universities in their own right.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In many countries, gaining an academic degree entitles the holder to assume distinctive academic dress particular to the awarding institution, identifying the status of the individual wearing them.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In many countries, degrees may only be awarded by institutions authorised to do so by the national or regional government.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Frequently, governments will also regulate the use of the word *university* in the names of businesses.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] This approach is followed, for example, by Australia, the United Kingdom and Israel.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The use of fake degrees by individuals, either obtained from a bogus institution or simply invented, is often covered by fraud laws.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Depending on the culture and the degree earned, degrees may be indicated by a pre-nominal title, post-nominal letters, a choice of either, or not indicated at all.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In countries influenced by the UK, post-nominal letters are the norm, with only doctorates granting a title, while titles are the norm in many northern European countries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Depending on the culture and the purpose of the listing, only the highest degree, a selection of degrees, or all degrees might be listed.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The awarding institution may be shown and it might be specified if a degree was at honours level, particularly where the honours degree is a separate qualification from the ordinary bachelor's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] For member institutions of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, there is a standard list of abbreviations for university names given in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In practice, many variations are used and the Yearbook notes that the abbreviations used may not match those used by the universities concerned.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Other Latin abbreviations commonly used include 'Cantuar' for Lambeth degrees (awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury), 'Dunelm' for Durham University, 'Ebor' for the University of York and 'Exon' for the University of Exeter.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] The Ancient universities of Scotland and the University of London have abbreviations that are the same in English and Latin.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Confusion can result from universities sharing similar names, e.g. the University of York in the UK and York University in Canada or Newcastle University in the UK and the University of Newcastle in Australia.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] In this case, the convention is to include a country abbreviation with the university's name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] For example, 'York (Can.)' and 'York (UK)' or 'Newc (UK)' and 'Newc (Aus.) are commonly used to denote degrees conferred by these universities where the potential for confusion exists, and institution names are given in this form in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Abbreviations used for degrees vary between countries and institutions, e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] MS indicates Master of Science in the US and places following American usage, but Master of Surgery in the UK and most Commonwealth countries, where the standard abbreviation for Master of Science is MSc.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Common abbreviations include BA and MA for Bachelor and Master of Arts, BS/BSc and MS/MSc for Bachelor and Master of Science, MD for Doctor of Medicine and PhD for Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p01] Improvements in technology, the increasing use of the Internet worldwide, and the need for people to have flexible school schedules that enable them to work while attending school have led to a proliferation of online colleges that award associate's, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Bangladesh and India mostly follow the colonial era British system for the classification of degrees, however, Pakistan has recently switched to the US model of a two-year associate degree and a four-year bachelor's degree program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The arts, referring to the performing arts and literature, may confer a Bachelor of Arts (BA) and a Master of Arts (MA).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Management degrees are also classified under 'arts' but are nowadays considered a separate stream, with degrees of Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) and Master of Business Administration (MBA).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Science refers to the basic sciences and natural science (Biology, Physics, Chemistry, etc.); the corresponding degrees are Bachelor of Science (BSc) and Master of Science (MSc).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Information Technology degrees are conferred specially in the field of computer science, and include Bachelor of Science in Information Technology (B.Sc.IT.) and Master of Science in Information Technology (M.Sc.IT.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The engineering degree in India follows two nomenclatures, Bachelor of Engineering (B.Eng.) and Bachelor of Technology (B.Tech.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Both represent bachelor's degree in engineering.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In Pakistan, engineering degrees are Bachelor of Engineering (B.E.) and Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.S./B.Sc.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Both are the same in curriculum, duration and pattern, and differ only in nomenclature.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The engineering degree in Bangladesh is a Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.Sc.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Indonesia follows a higher education system that originated from the Dutch colonial period.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] However, over the years, Indonesia has transitioned from the Dutch degree classification system and developed its own academic distinctions by translating and adapting its degree structure.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] All degrees in Indonesia follow standardized regulations.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The duration of each program is specified by Regulation of the Minister of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia Number 3 of 2020 on National Standards of Higher Education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The regulation outlines the maximum duration and minimum credit requirements (Semester Credit Units or SKS) for each level of study without counting academic leave.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The degree structure follows a standardized pattern, where XX represents the specific field of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Since a semester consists of 14 or 15 weeks of coursework and 1 or 2 weeks of exams, one SKS translates to an average of 40 hours of study per semester.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Comparatively, one European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credit equals 28 hours of study, meaning that one Indonesian SKS is approximately equivalent to 1.5 ECTS.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Therefore, a bachelor's degree in Indonesia (minimum 144 SKS) is roughly equivalent to 216 ECTS, which surpasses the standard European requirement of 180 ECTS for a bachelor's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] All degrees in Indonesia grant academic titles, which are often used in formal and social settings, including on unofficial documents such as marriage invitations.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Before Indonesia adopted its modern degree classification, the country used a system copied from the Dutch colonial academic structure, which in Netherlands remained extant to 2002.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In this system, university students typically studied for five years before graduating.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] This structure was different from the modern four-year bachelor's (S1) degree, as it allowed graduates to proceed directly to a doctorate (S3) program without first obtaining a master's (S2) degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] This system included pre-nominal academic titles that have largely been phased out but are still recognized, for those who graduated before 1992.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Some of these titles are still in limited use today.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Doktorandus (Drs.) and Doktoranda (Dra.) originated from Latin, meaning "one who is to become a doctor." These titles indicated that the degree holder only needed to complete a dissertation to obtain a doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Until the 1960s, diplomas from Bandung Institute of Technology (ITB) explicitly stated that holders were entitled to pursue a doctorate upon defending a thesis.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] After the 1970s, ITB replaced Doktorandus and Insinyur (Engineer) titles with Sarjana (Bachelor) degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] However, these titles remained granted and used until 1992 in other universities or institutes.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] By aligning with Anglo education standards, Indonesia transitioned to the B.Sc. - M.Sc. - Ph.D. model, similar to the Bologna Process.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Unlike the previous system, where five-year graduates could proceed directly to a Ph.D., students must now complete an S1 (Bachelor's) and S2 (Master's) before pursuing S3 (Doctorate).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Despite this transition, many pre-1992 graduates retained the use of their original titles granted upon their graduation, making formats such as Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Drs. [Name] common among senior academics and professionals.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Sri Lanka, like many other commonwealth countries, follows the British system, but with its own distinctions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Degrees are approved by the University Grants Commission.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Tunisia's educational grading system, ranging from elementary school to Ph.D. programs, operates on a scale of 0 to 20.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The minimum score for passing is set at 10 out of 20.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] This numerical system exclusively evaluates a student's academic accomplishments, serving as the determinant for admission into advanced programs.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] For instance, a student's grades obtained for their bachelor's degree are considered when they apply for a Master's program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Level 4 courses, which include the first year of a Bachelor's program or a Higher National Certificate (HNC), may allow students to enter directly into the second year of a Bachelor's program, provided that the course they completed is the same as the one they are applying for.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In South Africa, grades (also known as "marks") are presented as a percentage, with anything below 50% considered a failure.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Students who receive a failing grade may have the opportunity to rewrite the exam, depending on the criteria established by their institution.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Degrees in almost any field of study can be pursued at one of the institutions in the country, with certain institutions being known for excelling in specific fields.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Major fields of study across the country include Arts, Commerce, Engineering, Law, Medicine, Science, and Theology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) has developed a credit-based system for degrees, with different levels of National Qualifications Framework (NQF) ratings corresponding to each degree level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] For example, an undergraduate degree in Science is rated at NQF level 6, while an additional year of study in that discipline would result in an NQF level 8 (honours degree) rating.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In Kenya, the first undergraduate degree is pursued after students have completed four years of secondary school education and attained at least a C+ (55–59%) on the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Students pursuing a degree in engineering, such as B.Sc.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Electrical and Electronics Engineering, are required to join programs that are accredited by the Engineers Board of Kenya and the Commission for University Education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The B.Sc. degree in engineering typically takes five years to complete.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] A degree in medicine or surgery may take six to seven years, while a degree in education or management takes around four years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] For students pursuing a master's degree, they must have completed an undergraduate degree and attained at least a second-class honours upper division (60–69%) or lower division plus at least two years of relevant experience.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Most master's degree programs take two years to complete.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In an engineering master's degree program, students are typically required to publish at least one scientific paper in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] To pursue a doctor of philosophy degree, students must have completed a relevant master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] They are required to carry out a supervised scientific study for a minimum of three years and publish at least two scientific first-author papers in peer-reviewed journals relevant to their area of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Currently, Kenya is implementing a Competency Based Curriculum (CBC) that follows a 2–6–3–3 education system to replace the existing 8–4–4 system which allows confirmation of undergraduate degrees upon successful completion.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] This system is gradually replacing the two-stage system previously used in some countries and is combined with other elements such as the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) and the use of Diploma Supplements to make comparisons between qualifications easier.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The European Higher Education Area (EHEA) was formally established in 2010 and, as of September 2016, has 50 members.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The implementation of the various elements of the EHEA varies between countries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Twenty-four countries have fully implemented a national qualifications framework, and a further ten have a framework but have not yet certified it against the overarching framework.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In 38 countries, ECTS credits are used for all higher education programmes, and 31 countries have fully implemented diploma supplements.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Only 11 countries have included all the major points of the Lisbon Recognition Convention in national legislation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Since 2008, the European Union has been developing the European Qualifications Framework (EQF).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] This is an eight-level framework designed to allow cross-referencing of the various national qualifications frameworks.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] While it is not specific to higher education, the top four levels (5–8) correspond to the short cycle, first cycle, second cycle, and third cycle of the EHEA.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The two-cycle degree system was phased out by 2010, with a few exceptions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] However, some of the established degree naming has been preserved, allowing universities to award the "Diplom-Ingenieur" (and for a while also the "Magister") to graduates of the new-style Master programmes.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] While higher education is regulated by the three communities of Belgium, all have common and comparable systems of degrees that were adapted to the Bologna structure during the 2000s.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The primary 3-cycle structure is called BMD (Bachelor-Master-Doctorate; French: *Bachelier-Master-Doctorat* or Dutch: *Bachelor-Master-Doctoraat*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In the first cycle, the Bachelor's degree is issued after 180 ECTS (3 years, EQF level 6).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Other first cycle degrees include the one-year Advanced Bachelor's degree degree (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor') and the Brevet (in the French-speaking Community only) for short-cycle higher education programmes.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Bachelor's degrees are followed in the second cycle (EQF level 7) by Master's degrees that last two years, completing an extra 120 ECTS credits.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The master's degree can be followed by an Advanced Master's degree (French: *Master de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] 'Specialized Master'; Dutch: *Master-na-master*, lit.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] 'Master-after-master') that lasts one year (60 ECTS).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The Czech Republic has implemented the Bologna process, and functionally has three degrees: Bachelor (3 years), Master (2 years after Bachelor) and Doctor (4 years after Master).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The Czech Republic also has voluntary academic titles called "small doctorates" (e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] RNDr. for natural sciences, PhDr. for philosophy, JUDr. for law etc.) which are achieved after passing an additional exam.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Medical students do not get bachelor's or master's degrees, but instead attend a six-year program and obligatory exam they achieve the title MUDr.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] (equivalent to MD degree in the United States of America), or MDDr. for dentists and MVDr. for veterinary physicians.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] They can also get a "big doctorate" (Ph.D.) after another three or four years of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and small doctorates in the form of letters (Bc., Mgr., Ing., ...) are listed before the person's name, and Doctor's degrees (Ph.D.) are listed after name (e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The Czech Republic previously had more degrees that were awarded.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Before the adoption of the Bologna Process, the lowest degree that would normally be studied at universities in Denmark was equivalent to a master's degree (*kandidatgrad*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Officially, a bachelor's degree was always obtained after 3 years' university studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Various medium-length (2–4 years) professional degrees have been adopted, so they now have status as professional bachelor's degrees of varying length.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] As opposed to academic bachelor's degrees, they are considered to be "applied" degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] A professional bachelor's degree is 180, 210, or 240 ECTS-points.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Historically, the Finnish higher education system is derived from the German system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The current system of higher education comprises two types of higher education institutions, the universities and the polytechnics, many of whom refer to themselves as universities of applied sciences (UAS).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] With the exception of a few fields, such as medicine and dentistry, the Finnish system of higher education degrees is in compliance with the Bologna process.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Universities award bachelor's degrees (*kandidaatti / kandidat*), Master's degrees (*maisteri / magister*) and doctoral degrees (*lisensiaatin tutkinto / licentiat examen* and *tohtorin tutkinto / doktorexamen*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In most fields, the system of doctoral degrees is two-tier, the degree of licentiate is an independent academic degree but completing the degree of doctor does not require completion of a licentiate degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The polytechnics (universities of applied sciences) have the right to award bachelor's and master's degrees; the degree titles are distinct from the titles used for university degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In general, students who are admitted to bachelor studies at a university have the right to continue to studies at master level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] At polytechnics, the right to continue to master-level studies has to be applied for separately and there is also a work experience requirement.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The majority of master's degree holders have graduated from university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The degrees awarded by the universities and polytechnics are at par by law, but the content and orientation of studies is different.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] A master's degree obtained at a polytechnic gives the same academic right to continue studies at doctoral level as a master's degree obtained at a university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The French national education system makes a distinction between a *diplôme national* ("national degree") and *diplôme universitaire* ("university degree").
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The former, which are considered to have a higher status, are controlled by the state and issued by universities on behalf of the responsible ministry; the latter are controlled and granted by the universities themselves.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Additionally, private universities and schools may be recognised by the state with a *diplôme visé* ("recognised degree") and then, after five years of recognition, have their degrees validated by the state, the validation having to be renewed every six years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Historically, academic degrees were orientated towards research, and the vocational education system awarded only diplomas.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Since the implementation of the Bologna Process in France, the degree-granting system is being simplified: schools continue to grant their own diplomas, but the state's recognition in degree awarding is more important than before.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] However, in France there are diplomas that are not recognised as degrees, such as specific diplomas designed by colleges (*écoles supérieures*), like the *mastère spécialisé* (accredited by the *Conférence des Grandes Écoles* but not automatically by the French Government).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Since 2002, *grande école* diplomas have been able to award a university degree, such as the Sciences Po *Bachelor*, which is a state-accredited diploma that awards a bachelor's degree (*Licence* in French).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] The recognised degrees are in three levels, following the Qualifications Framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] These are the *licence* (first level), *master* (second level) and *doctorat* (third level).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] All licence degrees take 3 years (180 ECTS credits) and all master's degrees take 2 years (120 ECTS credits).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] There are also 5-year (300 ECTS credits) engineer's degrees, which are master's degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] In addition to the doctorate, which is always a research degree, the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur en médicine* and the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur vétérinaire* are third level qualifications and recognized as level 7 in EQF.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] Traditionally in Germany, students studied for four to six years and then graduated with either a *Magister* degree (usually in subjects like humanities, linguistics or the arts) or a *Diplom* degree (typically in fields such as natural sciences, economics, or engineering).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p02] These qualifications were usually the first and highest academic degrees students earned before a doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Both Magister and Diplom degrees from universities required a final thesis and are generally considered equivalent to a modern master’s degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, the Diplom awarded by a *Fachhochschule* (university of applied sciences) is usually considered comparable to a bachelor’s degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] A different type of qualification in Germany is the *Staatsexamen* (state examination).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This is not an academic degree but a government licensing examination required for certain professions, such as doctors, teachers, lawyers, judges, and pharmacists.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Students typically study at university for three to six years before taking the first Staatsexamen, depending on their field.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] After passing the first Staatsexamen, candidates in fields like law and teaching must complete a practical training period called the *Vorbereitungsdienst* (preparatory service), which usually lasts about two years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] They then take a second Staatsexamen, which tests their practical skills.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In some cases, students of law or pharmacy can choose to graduate with a master’s degree instead of taking the first Staatsexamen.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Since 1999, Germany has replaced its traditional university degrees with bachelor’s and master’s degrees as part of the Bologna process.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This reform aimed to make degrees more comparable internationally and to shorten the overall time students spend in higher education, as older programs often took five years or more to complete.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Today, students typically complete a bachelor’s degree followed by a master’s degree; the first usually taking 3 years, and the latter taking 18 months to 2 years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Some universities resisted the change, but by the end of 2007 all institutions were required to adopt the new system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Degree programs that lead to a Staatsexamen (state examination), such as those in law or medicine, were generally not converted to the bachelor’s/master’s system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In Germany, doctoral degrees are awarded with different titles depending on the subject area.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Examples include Doktor der Naturwissenschaften (Doctor of Natural Sciences), Doktor der Rechtswissenschaften (Doctor of Law), Doktor der Medizin (Doctor of Medicine), and Doktor der Philosophie (Doctor of Philosophy).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In German-speaking countries, it is common for people to list multiple doctorates and honorary titles, and sometimes even use them in formal address.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Students who have completed a Diplom, Magister, master’s degree, or Staatsexamen can usually continue on to a doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In some cases, particularly strong bachelor’s graduates may also be admitted directly to a doctoral program after passing an aptitude assessment set by the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Doctoral degrees (such as Dr. rer. nat. or Dr. phil.) are the highest academic qualifications in Germany and are typically based on independent research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] (Doctor of Medicine): medical doctors often complete their doctoral thesis shortly after finishing their studies, and it may involve less independent research compared to doctorates in other fields.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Unlike some countries such as the United Kingdom, Germany does not have a system of “higher doctorates” (such as the Doctor of Science).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The Habilitation is an additional qualification beyond the doctorate, although it is not an academic degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It demonstrates the ability to carry out advanced research and teach at the university level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] To obtain a Habilitation, candidates usually write a second thesis (called a *Habilitationsschrift*) or submit a collection of significant research publications.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Once completed, the qualification is sometimes abbreviated as “habil.” after a person’s name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Traditionally, the Habilitation was required to become a *Privatdozent* (a university lecturer qualified to teach independently) and to pursue a professorship.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Today, universities no longer require it, although it can still be an advantage in more traditional academic fields.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In Greece access to university is possible after national exams (Panhellenic Exams).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Ireland operates under a National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The school-leaving qualification attained by students is called the Leaving Certificate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It is considered as Level 4–5 in the framework.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This qualification is the traditional route of entry into third-level education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] There are also Level 5 qualifications in certain vocational subjects (e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Level 5 Certificate in Restaurant Operations) awarded by the Further Education and Training Awards Council (FETAC).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Advanced Certificates at Level 6 are also awarded by FETAC.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These are completed in institutes of technology or universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In Italy access to university is possible after gaining the *Diploma di Maturità* at 19 years of age, following 5 years of study in a specific high school focused on certain subjects (e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] After gaining the diploma one can enter university and enrol in any curriculum (e.g. physics, medicine, chemistry, engineering, architecture): all high school diplomas allow access to any university curriculum, although most universities have pre-admission tests.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In addition to academic degrees, many professional qualifications are tied to the QTI at the different levels.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The first level, tied to the first cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea* (bachelor's degree) in universities and the *Diploma accademico di primo livello* in AFAM institutions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The *laurea* is obtained after three years of study (180 ECTS credits) and confers the academic title of *dottore*; the older university qualifications at this level took two to three years, with the three-year courses conferring the title of *dottore*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The second level, tied to the second cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* of university institutions, and the *Diploma accademico di secondo livello* of AFAM institutions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* is mapped to this level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The *Laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* are obtained after two further years of study (120 ECTS credits) and give the academic title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* took four to six years but was accessed directly from school, with a possible reduction by one year for those with a related *diploma* and also granted the title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The third level, tied to the third cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *Dottorato di ricerca* from university institutions and the *Diploma accademico di formazione alla ricerca* from AFAM institutions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The old *Dottorato di ricerca* and *Diploma di specializzazione* are tied to this level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The *Dottorato di ricerca*, under both new and old systems, takes a minimum of three years after the *laurea magistralie/specialistica*, and gives the academic titles of *Dottore di Ricerca (Dott.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The old *Diploma di specializzazione* took two to six years and gave the academic title of *Specialista*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The *Diploma di specializzazione*, which is offered in a few specific professions, takes two to six years and gives the title of *specialista*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The *Diploma di perfezionamento* is a university certificate, aimed at professional training or in specific fields of study, which usually takes one year; it is not allocated a level in the framework.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] AFAM institutions may offer the *Diploma di perfezionamento o Master* and *Diploma accademico di specializzazione*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These are one-year and two-year qualifications, respectively, and may be offered at the second cycle or third cycle level, distinguished by adding *(I)* or *(II)* after the qualification name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Higher schools for language mediators offer the *Diploma di mediatore linguistico*, a first-cycle degree that takes three years (180 ECTS credits), and which gives access to the *laurea specialistica*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Specialisation institutes/schools in psychotherapy offer the *Diploma di specializzazione in psicoterapia*, a third-cycle qualification that takes at least four years and requires a *laurea magistrale/specialistica* in either psychology or medicine and surgery, along with professional registration.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In the Netherlands, the structure of academic studies was altered significantly in 1982 when the "Tweefasenstructuur" (Two Phase Structure) was introduced by the Dutch Minister of Education, Wim Deetman.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] With this structure an attempt was made to standardise all the different studies and to have them conform to similar timetables.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] An additional effect was that students would be forced to produce results within a preset time-frame or otherwise discontinue their studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The two-phase structure has been adapted to a bachelor-master structure as a result of the Bologna process.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In order for a Dutch student to get access to a university education, the student must complete a six-year pre-university secondary education called *voorbereidend wetenschappelijk onderwijs* (VWO).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] There are other routes possible, but only if the educational level of the applicant is comparable to that at the end of the standard two levels is access to university education granted.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] For some studies, specific end levels or disciplines are required, e.g., graduating without having studied physics, biology and chemistry will make it impossible to study medicine.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] People 21 years old, or older, who do not have the required entrance diplomas, may opt for an entrance exam to be admitted to a higher-educational curriculum.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In this exam, they have to prove their command of disciplines considered necessary for pursuing such study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] After 1 September 2002, they would be thus admitted to a Bachelor's curriculum, not to a Master's curriculum.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] For some disciplines in the Netherlands, a governmentally determined limited access is in place (although under political review for abolishment, as of February 2011).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This limits the number of applicants to a specific course of study, thus trying to control the number of future graduates.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The disciplines most renowned for their numerus clausus are medicine and dentistry.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Every year a combination of the highest pre-university graduation grades and some additional conditions determine who can start such a numerus clausus course of study and who can not.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Almost all Dutch universities are government supported, with only a few privately owned universities in existence (i.e. one in business and all others in theology).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Leiden University is the oldest, founded in 1575.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] For medical students the "doctorandus" degree is not equivalent to the European Anglo Saxon postgraduate research degree in medicine, of MD (Medical Doctor).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Besides the title doctorandus, the graduates of the Curius curriculum may also bear the title *arts* (physician).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The doctorandus in medicine title is granted after four years (nominal time) of the Curius curriculum, while the title physician is granted after six years (nominal time) of that curriculum.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The Dutch physician title is equal to a MSc degree according to the Bologna process and can be compared with the MBBS in the UK degree system and the North American MD, but not the UK MD degree, which is a research degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] One-on-one equivalence or interchangeability of the Dutch medical title and MD is often suggested.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, officially the MD title is not known, nor legal to use, in the Netherlands.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The correct notation for a Dutch physician who completed his or her medical studies, but did not pursue a doctoral (PhD-like) study is "drs." (e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Jansen, arts*) and not "dr." in medicine, which is often used incorrectly.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, like in the United Kingdom, physicians holding these degrees are referred to as 'Doctor' by courtesy.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In the Netherlands, there is the informal title *dokter* for physicians, but not *doctor* (dr.), unless they also earn such adegree by completing a PhD curriculum.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Furthermore, the *doctorandus* degree does not give a medical student the right to treat patients; for this a minimum of two years of additional study (internship) is required.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] After obtaining a Medical Board registration, Dutch physicians must work an additional two to six years in a field of expertise to become a registered medical specialist.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Dutch surgeons commonly are only granted access to surgical training and positions after obtaining a doctorate (PhD) successfully.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In recent years, the six-year (nominal time) old Curius curriculum (which offered the titles doctorandus and physician) has been replaced with a three-year (nominal time) Bachelor Curius+ followed by a three-year (nominal time) Master Curius+.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Those who had already begun their old-style Curius curriculum before that will still have to complete it as a six-year study (nominal time).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] A doctorandus in law uses the title *meester* (master, abbreviated as *mr.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Jansen*) instead of drs., and some courses of study, such as in technology and agriculture< grant the title *ingenieur* (engineer, noted as *ir.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These titles as equivalent to an LL.M (the title "mr.") and to a MSc (the title "ir.") and if gotten before 1 September 2002, from a recognized Dutch university, may be rendered as M (from Master) behind one's name, instead of using the typical Dutch honorifics before one's name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, this M is hardly used in favor of the typical Dutch titles ("drs.", "ir.", "mr."), or MSc, MA or LLM.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Since 1 September 2002, Dutch universities offer specific BSc, BA or LLB studies followed by MSc, MA or LLM studies, thus integrating into the international scientific community, offering lectures, other classes, seminars or complete curricula in English instead of Dutch.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] According to their field of study, MSc graduates may use either ir. or drs. before their names; MA graduates may use drs. before their name; LLM graduates may use mr. before their names, but only if they received such degrees from recognized Dutch universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Not uncommonly, the Dutch "drs." abbreviation can cause much confusion in other countries, since it is perceived as a person who has a PhD in multiple disciplines.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In the Netherlands, the degree MPhil was not awarded after 2009 as the Universiteiten van Nederland refused to recognize the MPhils awarded by Leiden University.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] After successfully obtaining a "drs.", "ir." or "mr." degree, a student has the opportunity to follow a further, promotional course of study (informally called PhD) to eventually obtain a doctorate and subsequently the title "doctor".
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Promotion studies are ideally structured according to a preset time schedule of 4 to 6 years, during which the student has to be mentored by at least one professor.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The promotion study has to be concluded with at least a scientific thesis, which has to be defended to "a gathering of his/her peers", in practice the board of the faculty with guest professors from other faculties or universities added.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] More and more common—and, in some disciplines, even mandatory—is that the student write, and have accepted for publication by peer-reviewed journals, original scientific work.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The number of publications required is often debated and varies considerably between the various disciplines.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, in all disciplines the student is obligated to produce and publish a dissertation or thesis in book form.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] All current Dutch academic programs are offered under the Anglo-Saxon bachelor/master structure.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It takes three years to earn a bachelor's degree and another one or two years to earn a master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] There are three official academic bachelor titles (BA, BSc and LLB) and three official master titles (MA, MSc and LLM).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These academic titles are protected by the Dutch government.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] After obtaining a doctorate, Dutch doctors may bear either the title dr.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] (lower case) before, or the letter D following, their name, but not both simultaneously.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] There is no notation signifying the specific discipline in which the doctorate is obtained.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] As of 1 January 2021, the title 'PhD' and post-nominal degree 'PhD' can also be used, and these are also legally protected.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Stacking of titles, as seen in countries such as Germany (Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Gruber), is highly uncommon in the Netherlands and not well received culturally.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Those who have multiple doctoral titles may use dr.mult. before their name, but this is seldom seen in practice.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The *honoris causa* doctors may use dr.h.c. before their name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Combining different Dutch titles, especially in different disciplines, is allowed, however, (e.g. mr. dr.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The use of the combination ir. ing. is frequent, indicating one holds a HBO, vocational, or professional engineering degree "ing.", together with an academic engineering degree "ir.".
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] What is not allowed is, after obtaining a doctorate, using dr. drs.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] A combination of a Dutch title with an international title is not allowed, except for some limited number of international professional titles.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Thus, one should choose either one's classical Dutch title or use the shortcut provided by the law following one's name (since 1 September 2002 it is the other way around: those who hold Dutch degrees as MSc, LLM or MA may optionally use the old-style shortcuts before their names).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] "*Doctors*" (dr.) can proceed to teach at universities as "universitair docent" (UD – assistant professor).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] With time, experience and achievement, this can evolve to a position as "universitair hoofddocent" (UHD – associate professor).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Officially an UHD still works under the supervision of a "hoogleraar" (professor), the head of the department.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, this is not a given; it is also possible that a department is headed by a "plain" doctor, based on knowledge, achievement and expertise.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The position of "hoogleraar" is the highest possible scientific position at a university and equivalent to the US "full" professor.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The Dutch professor's title, noted as *prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Jansen* or *professor Jansen*, is connected to one's employment.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This means that, should the professor leave the university, he or she also loses the privilege to use the title of professor.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Retired professors are an exception and may continue to note the title in front of their name, or use the title emeritus professor (em. prof.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] People who switch to a non-university job lose their professorial title and are only allowed to use the "dr." abbreviation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Unlike some other European countries, such as Germany, Dutch academic titles are used rarely outside academia, hold no value in everyday life, and typically are not listed on official documentation (e.g. passport, drivers license, (governmental) communication).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Dutch academic titles, however, are legally protected and can only be used by graduates from Dutch institutions of higher education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Illegal use is considered a misdemeanor and is subject to legal prosecution.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Holders of foreign degrees, therefore, need special permission before being able to use a recognised Dutch title, but they are free to use their own foreign title (untranslated).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In practice, the Public Department does not prosecute the illegal use of a protected title (the Netherlands applies prosecutorial discretion, so some known criminal uses are not prosecuted).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Prior to 1980, there were around 50 different degrees and corresponding educational programs within the Norwegian higher education system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Degrees had titles that included the gender based Latin term *candidatus/candidata*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The second part of the title usually consisted of a Latin word corresponding to the profession or training.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] (Candidatus Magisterii) required 4 to 5 years, Cand.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] (Candidatus Realium) required 6 years of study and a scientific thesis in a select set of scientific disciplines (realia).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Over the years these were replaced gradually with degrees that were more and more internationally comparable programs and corresponding titles.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These degrees were all retired in 2003 in favour of an international system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The reform of higher education in Norway, *Kvalitetsreformen* ("The Quality Reform"), was passed in the Norwegian Parliament, the Storting, in 2001 and carried out during the 2003/2004 academic year.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It introduced standard periods of study and the titles *master* and *bachelor (baccalaureus)*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The system differentiates between a free master's degree and a master's degree in technology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The latter corresponds to the former *sivilingeniør* degree (not to be confused with a degree in civil engineering, which is but one of many degrees linked to the title *sivilingeniør*, which is still in use for new graduates who can choose to also use the old title).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] All pre-2001 doctoral degree titles were replaced with the title "Philosophical Doctor degree", written *philosophiæ doctor* (instead of the traditional *doctor philosophiæ*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The title dr. philos. is a substantially higher degree than the PhD and is reserved for those who qualify for such a degree without participating in an organized doctoral degree program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In Poland, the system is similar to the German one.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Since 1992, Russian higher education has introduced a multilevel system, enabling higher education institutions to award and issue Bachelor of Science and Master of Science degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In Russia, Ukraine and some other former USSR republics educational degrees are awarded after finishing a college education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] There are several levels of education that one must choose in the 2nd and 3rd year of college, usually in the 3rd year of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] A specialist degree is awarded after 5 years of college (4 + 1).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] A Master's (Magister) degree is awarded after 6 years of college (4 + 2).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] But a Specialist degree can appear equivalent to Magister degree by reason of taking an equivalent amount of time.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Usually Specialist or Magister degrees incorporate the bachelor's degrees in them, but only the high-level degree is given on the final diploma.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Specialist and Magister degrees require taking final state exams and producing written work on practical application of studied skills or research thesis (usually 70–100 pages) and is roughly equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The first-level academic degree is called *Candidate of Sciences* ("Kandidat Nauk").
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Finally, there is a *Doctor of Sciences* ("Doktor Nauk") degree in Russia and some former USSR academic environments.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This degree is granted for contributions in a certain field (formally – who established new direction or new field in science).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It requires discovery of new phenomenon or development of new theory or essential development of new direction, etc.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] There is no equivalent of this "doctor of sciences" degree in the US academic system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It is roughly equivalent to Habilitation in Germany, France, Austria and some other European countries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Candidate of Sciences* should be considered for recognition at the level of the first doctoral degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] According to *Guidelines for the recognition of Russian qualifications in the other countries*, in countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of the second doctoral degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In countries in which only one doctoral degree exists, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of this degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] LL.D. to *Candidate of Sciences of Legal Science*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Spain's higher-education legal framework includes official and accredited education, as well as non-official education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] In Spain, accreditation of official university study programmes is regulated by law and monitored by governmental agencies responsible for verifying their quality and suitability for official approval and accreditation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Official professional study programmes lead to degree qualifications (*Títulos*) with full academic and professional rights.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Master's Degree (*Master Universitario*) – 60 to 120 ECTS Credits in 1–2 years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Doctoral degree PhD (*Doctorado*) – in 3–4 years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Accredited bachelor's degrees and master's degrees qualifications will always be described as *Grado* and *Master Universitario*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These qualifications comply with the European Higher Education Area (EHEA) framework.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Officially approved and accredited university study programmes by law must implement this framework in order to attain and retain accreditation in Spain.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Not all EHEA-compliant study programmes in Spain are officially approved or accredited by government agencies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Some universities offer proprietary study programmes as alternatives for a variety of reasons: serving the continuing education market for individual self-advancement and also providing higher education to individuals who have failed to acquire bachelor's degree qualifications.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The main reason for offering these alternative studies, though, is the complex bureaucratic process required to receive the approval of specific titles, in particular when it refers to new studies or studies about matters that do not fit with the official studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] For historical reasons, the academic system has been very much under the control of the state, and private universities are still regarded with as a threat to the state system.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These programmes fall within the category of "non officially approved and accredited" or *estudios no oficiales*, and they confer no academic or professional rights.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This means that they do not entitle the bearer to claim to have any specific academic or professional qualifications, as far as the Spanish authorities are concerned.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, there may be private agreements to recognize the titles.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Universities offering non-official study programmes are legally bound to clearly differentiate between officially-approved and non-officially-approved qualifications.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Non-accredited master's degrees will be described as just *Master*, without the accompanying *Universitario*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Certain non-officially approved and accredited study programmes may acquire a positive reputation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] However, neither professional associations, government agencies, judiciary authorities, nor universities – other than the study programme provider – are obliged to recognize non-official qualifications in any way.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] All study programmes must be accredited by ANECA prior to their inclusion in the RUCT.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The RUCT records all officially approved universities and their bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and PhDs and each and every one of the officially approved and accredited study programmes.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Universities are assigned a specific number Code (*Código*) by the RUCT.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The same study programme may acquire different codes as it progresses through various stages of official approval by local and central governments.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Prospective students should check the RUCT Code awarded to the study programme of their interest at every stage of their enquiries concerning degrees in Spain.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] ANECA makes recommendations regarding procedures, staffing levels, quality of teaching, resources available to students and continuity or loss of accreditation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The ANECA Registry records all events in the life of an officially approved and accredited study programme or a university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The ANECA Registry Search Facility may be the simplest and safest way to verify the status of all officially approved and accredited study programmes in Spain.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] It is also possible to track qualifications by using the search facility that several Autonomous Communities' own accreditation agencies offer.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The qualifications framework for higher education MECES is the reference framework adopted in Spain in order to structure degree levels.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Not all universities offer degrees named exactly the same, even if they have similar academic and professional effects.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Each university may present proposals for the study programme considered to meet professional and academic demand.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] The proposal will consist of a report linking the study programme being considered and the proposed qualification to be awarded.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] This report will be assessed by ANECA and sent for the Consejo de Universidades Españolas.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] If the *Consejo* agrees with ANECA's approval, it will be included in the RUCT and ANECA registries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] All bachelor's and master's degrees accredited by ANECA bestow full academic and professional rights in accordance with new and previous laws.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Professional-practice law in Spain is currently under revision.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Before the Bologna Process, the academic degree of a Licentiate was reached after 4 or 5 years of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Depending on the official language of the university, it was called *Lizentiat* (German), *Licence* (French) or *licenza* (Italian) and, according to the Bologna reform, is today considered equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] A Licentiate with a predefined qualification gave access to the last stage of a further two or more years of studies (depending on the field) for a doctoral degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Apart from this, most universities offered a postgraduate diploma requiring up to two years of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] French-speaking universities called them *diplôme d'études approfondies* DEA or DESS, the Italian-speaking university *post laurea* and German-speaking universities mostly *Nachdiplomstudium* (NDS).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Today the federal legislation defines these postgraduate diplomas (60 ECTS credits) as Master of Advanced Studies (MAS) or Executive Master of Business Administration (EMBA) degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Universities may also offer the possibility to gain a diploma in advanced studies (DAS, less than 60 ECTS credits).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] These degrees do not normally give access to a doctoral programme.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Turkish education system has been mostly compatible with the Bologna process before and immediately after adoption.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] New graduates of a bachelor's program from Turkish law faculties are required to enter a legal licensing examination from 2022 onwards, in order to use all the rights to the extent that has been granted by the related laws.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p03] Such requirement does not exist for other degree holders.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] An academic degree is protected under UK law.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] All valid UK degrees are awarded by universities or other degree-awarding bodies whose powers to do so are recognised by the UK government; hence they are known as "recognised bodies".
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The standard first degree in England, Northern Ireland and Wales is the bachelor's degree conferred with honours.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Usually this is a Bachelor of Arts (BA) or a Bachelor of Science (BSc) degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Other variants exist: for example, Bachelor of Education or Bachelor of Laws.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] It usually takes three years to read for a bachelor's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Candidates who have not achieved the standard for the award of honours may be admitted without honours to the "ordinary" bachelor's degree if they have met the required standard for this lesser qualification (also referred to as a "pass degree").
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Standard levels for each of these classes are 70%+ for a first, 60–69% for a 2:1, 50–59% for a 2:2, 40–49% for a 3rd and 30%+ for a pass degree, although this can vary by institution (e.g. the Open University).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The foundation degree is a qualification, lower than bachelor's level, awarded following a two-year programme of study that is usually vocational in nature.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The foundation degree can be awarded by a university or college of higher education that has been granted foundation-degree-awarding powers by the UK government.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] This degree is comparable to an associate degree in the United States.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The universities of Oxford and Cambridge award honorary Master of Arts (MA) degrees to graduates of their bachelor's programmes, following a specified period of time.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] This is comparable to the practice of the ancient universities in Scotland awarding an MA for a first degree and arguably reflects the rigorous standards expected of their graduates.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Master's degrees such as Master of Arts or Master of Science are typically awarded to students who have undertaken at least a year of full-time postgraduate study, which may require study and involve an element of research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Degrees such as Master of Philosophy (MPhil) or Master of Letters/Literature (MLitt) are likely to be awarded for postgraduate study involving original research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] A student undertaking a master's would normally be expected to already hold a bachelor's degree in a relevant subject, hence the possibility of reaching the master's level in one year.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Some universities award a master's as a first degree following an integrated programme of study (an 'integrated master's degree').
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These degrees are usually designated by the subject, such as Master of Engineering for engineering, Master of Physics for physics, Master of Mathematics for mathematics and so on; it usually takes four years to read for them.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Graduation to these degrees is always with honours.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Master of Engineering in particular has now become the standard first degree in engineering at the top UK universities, replacing the older Bachelor of Engineering.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree is highly valued by those seeking to advance in business as managers and decision makers.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctoral degrees or doctorates, such as the Doctor of Philosophy degree (PhD or DPhil) or Doctor of Education (EdD or DEd), are awarded following a programme of original research that contributes new knowledge within the context of the student's discipline.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctoral degrees usually take three years full-time.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Therefore, in the UK it may only take seven years to progress from undergraduate to earning a doctorate – in some cases six, since having a master's is not always a precondition for embarking on a doctoral degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] This contrasts with nine years in the United States, reflecting differences in the educational systems.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Some doctorates, such as the Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy) qualification, confirm competence to practice in particular professions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] UK post-secondary qualifications are defined at different levels, with levels 1–3 denoting further education and levels 4–8 denoting higher education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Within this structure, a foundation degree is at level 5; a bachelor's degree at level 6; a master's degree at level 7; and a doctoral degree at level 8.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Full information about the expectations for different types of UK degrees is published by the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] See also graduate certificate, graduate diploma, postgraduate certificate, postgraduate diploma and British degree abbreviations.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The standard first degree for students studying arts or humanities in Scotland is either a Bachelor of Arts or a Master of Arts (the latter traditionally awarded by the Ancient Universities of Scotland for a first degree in an arts/humanities subject).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The standard undergraduate degree for natural and social science subjects is the Bachelor of Science.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Students can work towards a first degree at either ordinary or honours level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] A general or ordinary degree (BA/MA or BSc) takes three years to complete; an honours degree (BA/MA Hons or BSc Hons) takes four years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The ordinary degree need not be in a specific subject, but can involve study across a range of subjects within (and sometimes beyond) the relevant faculty, in which case it may also be called a general degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] If a third year or junior honours subject is included, the ordinary degree in that named discipline is awarded.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The honours degree involves two years of study at a sub-honours level in which a range of subjects within the relevant faculty are studied and then two years of study at honours level which is specialised in a single field (for example classics, history, chemistry, biology, etc.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Not all universities in Scotland adhere to this; in some, one studies in several subjects within a faculty for three years and can then specialise in two areas and attain a joint honours degree in fourth year.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] This also reflects the broader scope of the final years of Scottish secondary education, where traditionally five Highers are studied, compared to (typically) three English or Welsh A-Levels.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The Higher is a one-year qualification, as opposed to the two years of A-Levels, which accounts for Scottish honours degrees being a year longer than those in England.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Advanced Highers add an optional final year of secondary education, bringing students up to the level of their A-Level counterparts – students with strong A-Levels or Advanced Highers may be offered entry directly into the second year at Scottish universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Students who complete all the requirements for an honours degree, but who do not receive sufficient merit to be awarded third-class honours, may be awarded a *Special Degree* (ordinary degree – bachelor's level SCQF Level 9).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In most respects, the criteria for awarding qualifications at honours level and above are the same as in the rest of the UK (see above under England, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Postgraduate qualifications are not designated Master of Arts, as in the rest of the UK, as this is an undergraduate degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Postgraduate degrees in arts and humanities subjects are usually designated Master of Letters (M.Litt.) or, in natural and social sciences, Master of Science (M.Sc.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Non-doctoral postgraduate research degrees are usually designated Master of Philosophy (M.Phil.) or Master of Research (M.Res.).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The postgraduate teaching qualification is the Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In Canada, education is the responsibility of the provinces and territories, rather than the federal government.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] However, all of Canada follows the three-level bachelor's-master's-doctorate system common to the Anglophone world, with a few variations.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] A common framework for degrees was agreed between the provinces and territories in 2007.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Bachelor's degrees take normally three to four years, more commonly three years in Quebec (where they follow on from college courses rather than directly from secondary education).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Outside Quebec, three-year bachelor's degrees are normally ordinary degrees, while four-year bachelor's degrees are honours degrees; an honours degree is normally needed for further study at the master's level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Master's degrees take one to three years (in Quebec they normally take one and a half to two years).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctorates take a minimum of three years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Alone among Canadian provinces and territories, British Columbia offers two-year associate degrees, allowing credit to be transferred into a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In Canada, first professional degrees such as DDS, MD, PharmD and LLB or JD are considered bachelor's level qualifications, despite their often being named as if they were doctorates.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In the province of Quebec, the majority of students must attend college prior to entering university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Upon completion of a two-year pre-university program, such as in sciences or humanities, or a three-year technical program, such as nursing or computer science, college graduates obtain a *college diploma*, which is a prerequisite for access to university-level studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Although these college programs are typical, they are not offered in every institution in the province.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Moreover, while a few other pre-university programs with various concentrations exist, many other technical/career programs are available, depending on the college of choice.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] For example, Dawson College in Montreal has nearly sixty different programs leading to a college diploma.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Special programs, such as physical rehabilitation therapy, are offered in some colleges as well.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] A similar option is offered for college nursing graduates as they can pursue their studies in university to obtain a Bachelor of Nursing in two years (rather than the usual three or four years, depending on whether the student has completed a college diploma in Quebec).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Education in Mexico follows a three-degree system similar to that of Canada and the US.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The pre-university academic level is the *bachillerato* (also called *preparatoria*), similar to high school.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] They can also get the degree of "ingenieria" or "medico" as an engineer or MD, respectively.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] After receiving the *licenciatura*, students may take extra courses called *diplomados* (similar to a certification but issued by a university).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These courses last 4–12 months and are a means to further study without continuing to the next degree level, and are usually to demonstrate that students are staying up-to-date in their fields.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Most students stay at this level, but some choose to continue to the *maestría*, equivalent to the master's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Study at the *maestría* level takes 1–3 years and mandates completion of a thesis.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Post-graduate students in Mexico typically enter a master's program after a few years in the workforce and often continue working while studying.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Traditionally, students who have completed the *maestria* may continue on to the *doctorado* or the doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctoral study typically lasts 3–4 years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In recent years this schemes has become flexible such that in some PhD programmes, students are accepted before, or not completing, the course of study for a master's.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In the United States, since the late 19th century, the threefold degree system of bachelor's, master's, and doctorate has been in place but has evolved into a slightly different pattern from the European equivalent.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Department of Education now classifies degrees in six categories: associate degrees, bachelor's degrees, first professional degrees, master's degrees, intermediate graduate qualifications and research doctorates.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The standard academic progression remains bachelor's—master's—(research) doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] This timetable is only approximate, however, as students in accelerated programs can sometimes earn a bachelor's degree in three years or, on the other hand, a particular dissertation project might take four or more years to complete.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In addition, a graduate may wait an indeterminate time between degrees before candidacy in the next level or even an additional degree at a level already completed.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Therefore, there is no time limit on the accumulation of academic degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] By far the most common research doctorate is the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), comprising 98.1% of research doctorates in 2014.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The Doctor of Education (Ed.D.) made up 1.1% (not including Ed.D.s classified as professional degrees rather than research doctorates) and all other research doctorates were less than 1% in total.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Some schools, mostly junior colleges and community colleges and some four-year schools, offer an associate degree that takes two full years of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These may be in professional or academic fields, and the most common awards are the Associate of Arts (A.A.) and Associate of Science (A.S.) degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Articulation agreements may allow credit earned on an associate degree to be counted toward the completion of a bachelor's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The "first professional degree" is a graduate-level degree program designed to prepare graduates for professional practice in various fields other than academic scholarship and research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] First professional degrees require a minimum of two years of college-level education prior to entering the program and a minimum of six years of total college-level education (including that undertaken prior to entry) to complete the program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Most professional degree programs require a prior bachelor's degree for admission and many require seven or eight years of total study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] M.D., J.D. or D.O. are named as doctorates but should not be confused with research doctorates such as the Ph.D.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] First professional degrees should also not be confused with professional master's degrees such as the M.Arch. and M.B.A., which are classified as master's degrees, or with intermediate graduate qualifications that also bear the title of doctor, such as D.Min. or D.Psy.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Intermediate graduate qualifications lie between the master's level and doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] They include awards such as the Certificate of Advanced Study, Graduate Diplomas, Professional Engineer status, and Professional Diplomas, as well as specialist degrees such as Education Specialist, Doctor of Ministry, Doctor of Psychology and the Licentiate in Sacred Theology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In 21 US jurisdictions, religious institutions can be authorized to grant religious-exempt (rel. exmpt., rel. expt., etc.) degrees without accreditation or government oversight.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Such degrees are used primarily to attain church-related employment.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Traditionally, more men than women attended and earned degrees at the world's universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] A milestone was reached in the United States, according to the 2010 census, as women surpassed men in attaining master's degrees, for the first time.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The U.S. census reports that 10.5 million men have master's degrees or higher, compared with 10.6 million women.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The first year that women surpassed men in earning bachelor's degrees was 1996.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Students, the media, and the general public have shown much concern over the value of getting a higher degree in the US ever since the Great Recession of 2007.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Media coverage of the rising costs of higher education and increased student debt have also affected the public's perceptions of whether higher degrees are still worthwhile.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Statistics citing that college graduates make around $1 million more in their lifetimes than those who did not attend college and live longer, healthier lives work in favor of those who argue the continued value of higher degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Studies like the 2011 Learning Gains study by Arum and Roksa, on the other hand, reported that only 55% of students had any learning gains during their first two years of college, which favors the argument that investing in higher education may not still be worth it.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) covers 10 levels, of which levels 6–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Also included within the higher education system are: diplomas at level 5 (first year of a degree course); advanced diplomas, at level 6 (associate degree level); and graduate certificates and graduate diplomas, both of which are at level 8 (honours degree level).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In Australia, most degrees are issued ungraded, with bachelor's degrees with honours being the exception.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctorates in Australia may be research doctorates (normally titled PhDs), professional doctorates (normally titled to refer to the field of practice, e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctor of Engineering) or higher doctorates (also normally titled to refer to the field of practice).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Extended master's degrees are also allowed to have the word 'doctor' in their title if they are in certain fields, but they are not doctoral degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Like Australia, New Zealand has a 10-level qualifications framework (the New Zealand Qualifications Framework – NZQF) and a referencing exercise has found a one-to-one correspondence between the levels of the two frameworks.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] However, the names given to qualifications at different levels are not the same and New Zealand does not have associate degrees, thus only levels 7–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These are the bachelor's degree (level 7), bachelor honours degree (level 8), master's degree (level 9) and the doctoral degree (level 10).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In addition to these, the NZQF has certificates across levels 1–6, diplomas at levels 5 and 6, graduate certificates and graduate diplomas at level 7 (bachelor's), and postgraduate certificates and postgraduate diplomas at level 8 (honours).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Another referencing exercise, comparing the NZQF to the 10-level Irish National Framework for Qualifications, found that degrees were comparable but that further work was needed to improve compatibility at the sub-degree levels (1–6).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Non-degree qualifications at levels 7–9 were not included in the study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In New Zealand, master's degrees may be awarded with classified honours (1st, 2:1, 2:2, 3rd) or with distinction or merit.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Undergraduate students in Brazilian universities graduate either with a bachelor's degree, a licentiate degree or a technologist degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Bachelor degrees in Brazil normally take four or five years of full-time study to complete, with the exception of the human medicine course, which requires six years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Licentiate degrees normally take four-years, and are for students who want to qualify as school teachers.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] *Licenciatura* courses exist mostly in mathematics, humanities and natural sciences.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The technologist degree is available in technology-related fields and can be normally obtained in three years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These degrees are for entry into industry.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Admission as an undergraduate student to most top public or private universities in Brazil requires that the applicant pass a competitive entrance examination known as the Vestibular.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Contrary to what happens in the United States, candidates must declare their intended university major when they register for the Vestibular.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Although it is theoretically possible to switch majors afterwards (in a process known within the universities as *transferência interna*), that is actually quite rare in Brazil.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Undergraduate curricula tend to be more rigid than in the United States and there is little room to take classes outside one's major.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Individuals who hold either a bachelor's degree, licentiate or technologist are eligible for admission into graduate courses leading to advanced master's or doctor's degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Criteria for admission into master's and doctor's programs vary in Brazil.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Some universities require that candidates take entrance exams; others make admission decisions based solely on undergraduate transcripts, letters of recommendation and possibly oral interviews.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In most cases, however, especially for the doctorate, the candidate is required to submit a research plan, and one faculty member must agree to serve as supervisor before the candidate can be admitted into the program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] There are two types of post-graduate programs: *lato sensu* (specialization and MBAs) and *stricto sensu* (professional master's, master's, and doctorate).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Specializations or MBAs are courses that include taking a minimum number of graduate classes (minimum of 360 hours) but with no need to do research nor defend a thesis, only to present final work showing knowledge acquired.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] It is a professional level where theory and practice are focused broadly.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Professional master's or master's degrees usually take one to two years of full-time study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The emphasis of the thesis must be in adding some value to knowledge, but not necessarily in being original.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Doctoral degrees normally take four additional years of full-time study to complete.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Requirements for obtaining a doctor's degree include taking additional advanced courses, passing an oral qualifying exam, and submitting a longer doctoral dissertation which must represent a significant original contribution to knowledge in the field to which the dissertation topic is related.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] That contrasts with master's thesis, which, in addition to being usually shorter than doctoral dissertations, are not required to include creation of new knowledge or revision/reinterpretation of older views/theories.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The doctoral dissertation is examined in a final oral exam before a panel of at least two members (in the state of São Paulo the preferred number is five, while the other regions prefer three members), usually including one or two external examiners from another university or research institute.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In Colombia, the system of academic degrees is based in the British model, similar to the U.S. model.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] After completing their "bachillerato" (high school), students can take one of three options.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The first one is called a *profesional* (professional career), which is similar to a bachelor's degree requiring from four to 6 years of study according to the chosen program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The other option is called a *técnico* (technician); this degree consists of two and a half years of study and prepares the student for technical or mechanical labors.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Finally, the third option is called a *tecnólogo* (equivalent to associate degree) and consists of three years of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] After this, students, now called *profesional* (professionals), *técnicos* (technicians) or *tecnólogos* (associates), can opt for higher degrees.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Formal education after the bachelor's degree leads to the master's degree with the title of *maestro* and doctorate degrees, known as *doctorado* (doctorate).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The master's degree normally takes two years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Students also can take a specialization course, *especialización*, equivalent to a graduate certificate degree, after their bachelor's degree.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These programs, like in the U.S., are very popular, because it requires only one to two years of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] In Colombia, similar to the U.S. system, the students may not go directly to the *doctorado* without having the "master" degree first.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] After completing *enseñanza media* (high school), students receive a *Licenciatura de Enseñanza Media* (high school diploma), which is a requirement for higher education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Higher-education programs that provide a professional title but not an academic degree are referred to as *carreras técnicas*, which are similar in duration and scope to associate degree programs.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] These are often granted by educational institutions of the type *instituto profesional* (IP) or *centro de formación técnica* (CFT).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Academic degrees in Venezuela start with the *Certificado de Educación Básica* (Certificate of Basic Education), awarded upon completing the 9th grade.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The next degree is earned upon completing the 11th grade and confers the title of *Bachiller en Ciencias* (High School Graduate of Science), *Bachiller en Humanidades* (High School Graduate of Humanities) or *Técnico en Ciencias* (Science Technician).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Titles at the higher-education level usually depend on the institution handing them out.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Technical schools award the student with the title of *Técnico Superior Universitario* (university higher technician, to distinguish from science technician).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Universities award the student with the title of *ingeniero* (engineer) or with the title *licenciado* (licentiate) after completing a five-year program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The ingeniero degree requires more physics than the licenciado degree, but both take five years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Some higher-education institutions may award *diplomados* (diploma), but the time necessary to obtain one varies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Medical doctors are awarded the title "Médico Cirujano" after completing a 6-year course of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] Postgraduate education in Venezuela follows the conventions of the United States (being named "master's" and "doctorate" after the programs there).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The nature of academic degrees from ecclesiastical institutions of education is outlined in the apostolic constitution *Sapientia Christiana*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-degrees-p04] The core of degrees granted by pontifical universities consists of three levels: the first is the baccalaureate; the second is the licentiate; the third is the doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:university-of-fribourg/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The **Adam Mickiewicz University** (Polish: *Uniwersytet im.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adama Mickiewicza w Poznaniu*; Latin: *Universitas Studiorum Mickiewicziana Posnaniensis*) is a research university in Poznań, Poland.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Due to its history, the university is traditionally considered among Poland's most reputable institutions of higher learning, this standing equally being reflected in national rankings.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] It traces its origins to 1611, when under the Royal Charter granted by King Sigismund III Vasa, the Jesuit College became the first university in Poznań.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Poznań Society for the Advancement of Arts and Sciences which played an important role in leading Poznań to its reputation as a chief intellectual centre during the Age of Positivism and partitions of Poland, initiated founding of the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The inauguration ceremony of the newly founded institution took place on 7 May 1919 that is 308 years after it was formally established by the Polish king and on 400th anniversary of the foundation of the Lubrański Academy which is considered its predecessor.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Its original name was Piast University (Polish: *Wszechnica Piastowska*), which later in 1920 was renamed to University of Poznań (Polish: *Uniwersytet Poznański*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] During World War II staff and students of the university opened an underground Polish University of the Western Lands (Polish: *Uniwersytet Ziem Zachodnich*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1955 University of Poznań adopted a new patron, the 19th-century Polish Romantic poet Adam Mickiewicz, and changed to its current name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university is organized into six principal academic units—five research schools consisting of twenty faculties and the doctoral school—with campuses throughout the historic Old Town and Morasko.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university employs roughly 4,000 academics, and has more than 40,000 students who study in some 80 disciplines.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] More than half of the student body are women.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The language of instruction is usually Polish, although several degrees are offered in either German or English.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university library is one of Poland's largest, and houses one of Europe's largest Masonic collections, including the 1723 edition of James Anderson's *The Constitutions of the Free-Masons*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university is currently publishing over 79 research journals, most of them on Pressto publishing platform based on Open Journal System.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University Repository (AMUR) contains over 23,704 records of research publications and is one of the first research repositories in Poland.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University is a member of the European University Association, EUCEN, SGroup European Universities' Network, Compostela Group of Universities and EPICUR.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] On 28 October 1611, when under the Royal Charter granted by King Sigismund III Vasa, the Jesuit College became the first university in Poznań.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] These edicts were later affirmed with charters issued by King John II Casimir in 1650, and King John III Sobieski in 1678, the university in Poznań lasted until 1773.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Based on these charters, the university granted scholar degrees to its members.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The inauguration ceremony of the newly founded took place on 7 May 1919, that is 308 years after it was formally established by the Polish king and the 400th anniversary of the foundation of the Lubrański Academy which is considered its spiritual predecessor.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Its original name was Piast University (Polish: *Wszechnica Piastowska*), which later in 1920, was renamed to the University of Poznań (Polish: *Uniwersytet Poznański*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1920, sociologist Florian Znaniecki founded the first Polish department of sociology at the university, one of the first such departments in Europe.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In the same period of the university's history, botanist Józef Paczoski founded the world's first institute of phytosociology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] After the invasion of Poland, Poznań was annexed by Germany and the university was closed by the Nazis in 1939.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] It was reopened as a German university in 1941, which operated until 1944.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Staff and students of the Polish university, some of them expelled by Germans to Warsaw, opened an underground Polish University of the Western Lands (Polish: *Uniwersytet Ziem Zachodnich*), whose classes met in private apartments (see Education in Poland during World War II).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Many of the professors and staff were imprisoned and executed in Fort VII in Poznań, including professor Stanisław Pawłowski (rector in the years 1932–33).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Polish university reopened, in much smaller form, after the end of World War II.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1950, the Medical Faculty, including the Dentistry section and the Faculty of Pharmacy, were split off to form a separate institution, now the Poznań University of Medical Sciences.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1955, the University of Poznań adopted a new patron, the 19th-century Polish Romantic poet Adam Mickiewicz, and changed to its current name.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university's central administrative building is Collegium Minus, on the west side of Adam Mickiewicz Square at the western end of the street Święty Marcin.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Some teaching takes place in Collegium Maius, another of the aforementioned group of buildings (on ul.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Fredry), although this is mainly used by the medical university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Other buildings in the city centre include former communist party headquarters on Święty Marcin, Collegium Novum (used mainly for language teaching) on Al.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Niepodległości, and the university library on ul.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university also uses a number of other buildings in southern and western districts of Poznań.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] However, it is strongly developing its site at Morasko in the north of the city.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] As of 2006, the faculties of physics, mathematics and computer science, biology, geographical and geological science had moved to the new location.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 2015 they were joined by the faculty of history (Collegium Historicum Novum).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university also has external branches in other towns of western Poland, including Kalisz, Ostrów Wielkopolski and Słubice.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University maintains close cooperation with Viadrina European University, Germany.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The two universities jointly operate the Collegium Polonicum, located just opposite Viadrina on the Polish side of the Oder River.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] University owns a seasonal polar research station located in the Petuniabukta (Petunia Bay), in the Northern part of Billefjord, and central part of Spitsbergen island in the Svalbard archipelago.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] As of 2024, Adam Mickiewicz University owns and operates retreats in three historical palaces in the Wielkopolska region: the Rococo Ciążeń Palace (built in 1768), the Classicist Gułtowy Palace (built in 1786), and the Neo-Renaissance Palace in Obrzycko (built in 1862).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] At the start of the 2008/2009 academic year, the university had 46,817 undergraduates (including about 18,000 on weekend or evening courses), 1308 doctoral students, and 2247 other post-graduate students.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The number of undergraduates declined slightly between 2005 and 2008.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] At the end of 2008, the university had a total of 2892 teaching staff, including 257 full professors and 490 associate/assistant professors.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Adam Mickiewicz University is one of the top Polish universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] It was ranked by *Perspektywy* magazine as the third best Polish university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] International rankings such as ARWU and QS University Rankings rank the university as the fourth best Polish higher level institution.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] On the list of the best Emerging Europe and Central Asia universities compiled by QS University Rankings, the Adam Mickiewicz University was placed as 60th.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 2020, QS World University Ranking by Subject positioned the Adam Mickiewicz University as one of the best higher level institutions among the top 101–150 in Linguistics, 251–300 in English studies, 371 in Arts & Humanities and 551–600 in Physics & Astronomy, Chemistry and Biology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University's prestige and large class size have enabled it to graduate a large number of distinguished alumni.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Many AMU alumni are leaders and innovators in the business world, as well as prominents in society and the arts.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Its graduates include authors (Kazimiera Iłłakowiczówna, Ryszard Krynicki, Stanisław Barańczak), journalists (Adam Michnik, Max Kolonko), entrepreneurs (Jan Kulczyk, Grażyna Kulczyk); composer Jan A.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Kaczmarek, the recipient of the Academy Award for Best Original Score (2004); theatre practitioner Lech Raczak, film director Filip Bajon and literary critic and a music aficionado, Jerzy Waldorff.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] One of the most notable resistance fighters of the Home Army during Second World War, Jan Nowak-Jeziorański majored in economics in 1936, he worked as an assistant professor at the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Hanna Suchocka, 5th Prime Minister of Poland, first woman to hold this post in Poland and the 14th woman to be appointed and serve as prime minister in the world, graduated from university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Additionally, Kazimierz Marcinkiewicz, the 12th Prime Minister of Poland and Roman Giertych, the Deputy Prime Minister of Poland and Minister of National Education between 2006 and 2007, are graduates.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Three graduates of the university have served as Marshals of the Sejm and Senate of the Republic of Poland.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Bohdan Winiarski was one of the longest-serving Judges of the International Court of Justice (1946–1967) and between 1961 and 1964 its president.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Three of the school's graduates, including Alfons Klafkowski (1985–1989), Mieczysław Tyczka (1989–1993) and Julia Przyłębska (since 2016), have served as the Presidents of the Constitutional Tribunal of the Republic of Poland.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Three of the current fifteen members of the court graduated from AMU: Julia Przyłębska, Andrzej Zielonacki and Justyn Piskorski.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Additionally, the President of Poland, Andrzej Duda, refused to swear in Roman Hauser, former President of the Supreme Administrative Court of Poland and Krzysztof Ślebzak as the Tribunal's judges.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In the 1920s the German military began using a 3-rotor Enigma, whose security was increased in 1930 by the addition of a plugboard.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Polish Cipher Bureau sought to break it due to the threat that Poland faced from Germany, but its early attempts did not succeed.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Near the beginning of 1929, the Polish Cipher Bureau realized that mathematicians may make good codebreakers; the bureau invited math students at University of Poznań to take a class on cryptology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] After the class, the Bureau recruited some students to work part-time at a Bureau branch set up in Poznań for the students.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] On 1 September 1932, 27-year-old Polish mathematician Marian Rejewski and two fellow Poznań University mathematics graduates, Henryk Zygalski and Jerzy Różycki, joined the Bureau full-time and moved to Warsaw.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Their first task was to reconstruct a four-letter German naval cipher.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Recipients of honorary doctorates from the university include Marshal Józef Piłsudski, Marshal Ferdinand Foch, Marie Curie, Ignacy Paderewski, Roman Dmowski, Witold Hensel, Ernst Håkon Jahr, Al Gore, J.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Coetzee, Krzysztof Matyjaszewski, Robert Maxwell and Orhan Pamuk, the recipient of the 2006 Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Wisława Szymborska, recipient of the 1996 Nobel Prize in Literature, received a degree of Honorary Doctor of Letters of Adam Mickiewicz University in 1995, and it's the only honorary doctorate she has ever accepted.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The **Adolphe Merkle Institute (AMI)** is a research center in Fribourg, Switzerland focused on nanoscience.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The institute is named after the Swiss entrepreneur Adolphe Merkle who created the foundation that partially funded the institute.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Adolphe Merkle, an entrepreneur from Fribourg, established the Adolphe Merkle Foundation in 2007 with the goal of strengthening research and teaching at the University of Fribourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] His contribution of 100 million Swiss francs constitutes one of the most important private donations to support academic research in Switzerland.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] In 2008, the Adolphe Merkle Institute was founded under its first director, Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Peter Schurtenberger, formerly a professor in the Department of Physics at the University of Fribourg and then appointed as the chair of Experimental Physics and Nanoscience at the Institute.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] He developed the vision of an interdisciplinary institute that focuses on soft nanomaterials and combines fundamental and application-oriented research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Christoph Weder, who joined AMI as the chair for Polymer Chemistry and Materials in 2009, became director, serving until April 2022.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Schurtenberger left the institute to establish a new group at the University of Lund. he institute appointed Professors Alke Fink and Barbara Rothen-Rutishauser as co-chairs of BioNanomaterials, Prof.Ullrich Steiner was appointed as Professor of Soft Matter Physics, and Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Michael Mayer as Professor of Biophysics.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Steiner took over as institute director in May 2022, followed by Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Hans Jörg Limbach, who was appointed as the institute's Chair of Food Science and Technology the previous year, in June 2026.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Since 2014, AMI is located on the University of Fribourg's Pérolles campus.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The Institute is housed in two renovated buildings that were previously a private clinic and an additional modern construction.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] AMI is an interdisciplinary research center, focused on fundamental and application-oriented research in soft nano- and materials sciences.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The institute is headed by an executive director and executive board, who report to a scientific advisory board and institute council.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Administrative structures are said to be kept lean and AMI employs an industry liaison and technology transfer office for partners from industry and academia, and a communications officer.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] 40% of AMI staff are doctoral students and 20% postdoctoral researchers.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The emphasis on interdisciplinarity is also reflected in how the research groups are constituted.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] They do not adhere to the traditional distinction of fields in the natural sciences but rather have interdisciplinary topics as their research focus.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The principal investigators of the research groups have full professorships at the University of Fribourg's Faculty of Science and Medicine.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] They teach at the Master's level but have a decreased teaching load in order to dedicate more time towards research activities at AMI.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The Polymer Chemistry & Materials group is conducting research on stimuli-responsive or *smart* polymers, supramolecular systems, bio-inspired materials, nanocomposites, and polymer mechanochemistry.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The BioNanomaterials group's research focuses on bioprinting, hazard assessment of nanomaterials, nanoparticle analysis and nanobiomechanics.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The BioPhysics group's research includes nanopores for single molecule analysis, bio-inspired voltage generation and pore forming peptides.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The Soft Matter Physics group is investigating and manufacturing nanostructured materials made by polymer self-assembly, energy materials for solar cells and batteries, photonic and plasmonic effects arising from structured materials, bio-inspired materials and surfaces.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The Food Science and Technology group, created in 2025, operates at the intersection of physics, chemistry, and biotechnology, notably through the development of food materials and their characterization.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The Mechanoresponsive Materials Group focuses on developing optical probes for polymers and soft matter, particularly for the detection of mechanical damage in these materials, using high-resolution microscopy techniques and bio-inspired approaches.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The Quantum Sensing & Spin Chemistry group, funded by an ERC starting grant, focuses on the use of quantum sensors to investigate chiral‑induced spin selectivity, at the intersection of physics, chemistry and biology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] In 2023 the institute had 40 active research projects.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Topics of investigation include color generation in insects, soft worm-like robots, the development of guidelines for nanomaterials waste disposal, artificial muscles, squid-inspired materials damage detection, and electric eel-inspired membranes.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] For the master's students there is a strong early focus on 'hands-on' work in the AMI laboratories as well as the opportunity to join one of the research groups for their master's thesis.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] A summer internship program for undergraduate students from universities around the world is also present and is run in collaboration with the National Center of Competence in Research (NCCR) *Bio-Inspired Materials* of the Swiss National Science Foundation (SNF).
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] AMI is conducting both fundamental as well as application-oriented research in the field of soft nanomaterials, receiving part of its funding through industrial partnerships.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] In 2018 AMI spawned its first startup NanoLockin.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] AMI is involved with and headquarters the National Center of Competence in Research *Bio-Inspired Materials*, an interdisciplinary center for research and education around materials inspired by nature.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] INTEGRATE is a multidisciplinary research program funded by the European Innovation Council and the Swiss Secretariat for Education, Research, and Innovation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The main goal is to develop energy-autonomous prosthetics and robotic devices, and counts with the participation of the Eindhoven University of Technology, the University of Rome Tor Vergata, the CNRS, VELTHA and the Adolphe Merkle Institute.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] PIRE was a collaboration between AMI, Case Western Reserve University, the University of Delaware, the University of Chicago, and the University of California at San Diego.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The program was funded by the National Science Foundations of Switzerland and the US.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Its focus lied on developing functional materials inspired by desirable substances in nature.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The European Commission funded PlaMatSu as an Innovative Training Network (ITN) under the Horizon 2020 Marie Sklodowska-Curie Actions with nine PhD students at University of Fribourg (Switzerland) and AMI, University of Freiburg (Germany), and University of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] As industrial partners the ITN included BASF SE (Germany), Fischerwerke GmbH & Co.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] Tillwich GmbH (Germany), as well as VDI - The Association of German Engineers and Wikimedia CH as communication partners.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] CityCare was another ITN funded by the European Commission under the Horizon 2020 Marie Sklodowska-Curie Actions with three PhD students.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The projects investigated the damaging effects of air pollutants on the skin.
[src:university-of-fribourg/adolphe-merkle-institute] The EU-funded ULTRHAS brought together partners from Norway, Finland, Germany, and the Adolphe Merkle Institute with the goal to reveal the health threats posed by nanoparticles from different transport sources, and provide guidance for policy development to improve air quality and health.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The **University of Freiburg** (colloquially German: *Uni Freiburg*), officially the **Albert Ludwig University of Freiburg** (German: *Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg*), is a public research university located in Freiburg im Breisgau, Baden-Württemberg, Germany.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university was founded in 1457 by the Habsburg dynasty as the second university in Austrian-Habsburg territory after the University of Vienna.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Today, Freiburg is the fifth-oldest university in Germany, with a long tradition of teaching the humanities, social sciences and natural sciences and technology and enjoys a high academic reputation both nationally and internationally.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university is made up of 11 faculties and attracts students from across Germany as well as from over 120 other countries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Foreign students constitute about 18.2% of total student numbers.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg has been associated with figures such as Hannah Arendt, Rudolf Carnap, David Daube, Johann Eck, Hans-Georg Gadamer, Friedrich Hayek, Martin Heidegger, Edmund Husserl, Herbert Marcuse, Friedrich Meinecke, Edith Stein, Paul Uhlenhuth, Max Weber and Ernst Zermelo.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] As of October 2020, 22 Nobel laureates are affiliated with the University of Freiburg as alumni, faculty or researchers, and 15 academics have been honored with the highest German research prize, the Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize, while working at the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Originally Albrechts University, the university started with four faculties (theology, philosophy, medicine, and law).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Its establishment belongs to the second wave of university foundings in the German-speaking world in the late Middle Ages, like the University of Tübingen and the University of Basel (Switzerland).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Established by papal privilege (papal bull), the university in Freiburg actually was – like all or most universities in the Middle Ages – a corporation of the church body and therefore belonged to the Roman Catholic Church and its hierarchy.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The bishop of Basel consequently was its provost or chancellor (*Kanzler*), the bishop of Constance was its patron, and the real founder of the university was the sovereign, Archduke Albert VI of Austria, being the brother of Frederick III, Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] At its founding, the university was named after Albert VI of Austria.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] He provided the university with land and endowments, as well as its own jurisdiction.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Also he declared Albrechts University as the "county university" (German *Landesuniversität*) for his territory until it was handed over to the Austrian House of Habsburg in 1490.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university soon attracted many students, such as the humanists Geiler von Kaysersberg, Johann Reuchlin, and Jakob Wimpfeling.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] When Ulrich Zasius was teaching law (until 1536), Freiburg became a centre of humanist jurisprudence.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] From 1529 to 1535, Erasmus of Rotterdam after having left Basel, lived and taught in Freiburg, however, never at the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] From around 1559 on, the university was housed at the *Altes Collegium* ("Old College"), today called the "new town-hall".
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The importance of the university decreased during the time of the Counter-Reformation.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] To counter reformatory tendencies, the administration of two faculties was handed over to the Roman Catholic order of the Jesuits in 1620.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] From 1682 on, the Jesuits built their college, as well as the Jesuit church (nowadays the "University Church" or *Universitätskirche*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 1679, Freiburg temporarily became French territory, along with the southern parts of the upper Rhine.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] French King Louis XIV disliked the Austrian system and gave the Jesuits a free hand to operate the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] On 6 November 1684, a bilingual educational program was initiated.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] From 1686 to 1698, the faculty fled to Konstanz.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] After Freiburg was re-conquered and appointed as capital of Further Austria, a new time began for the university by the reforms of Empress Maria Theresa of Austria.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The requirements for admission were changed for all faculties in 1767 (before that time only Roman Catholics were allowed to study) and Natural Sciences were added as well as Public Administration.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Also in 1767, the university became a governmental institution despite the Church's protests.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The Church finally lost its predominant influence on the university when the Jesuits were suppressed following a decree signed by Pope Clement XIV in 1773.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Consequently, Johann Georg Jacobi (brother of the more famous philosopher Friedrich Heinrich Jacobi) in 1784 was the first Protestant professor teaching at the university in Freiburg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] When Freiburg became a part of the newly established Grand Duchy of Baden in 1805 (after Napoleon occupied the area of the formerly Further Austria), a crisis began for the university in Freiburg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university had enough endowments and earnings to survive until the beginning of the regency of Ludwig I, Grand Duke of Baden in 1818.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Finally in 1820, he saved the university with an annual contribution.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Since then, the university has been named Albert Ludwigs University of Freiburg (*Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg*) as an acknowledgement of gratitude by the university and the citizens of Freiburg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the 1880s, the population of the student body and faculty started to grow quickly.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The scientific reputation of Albert Ludwigs University attracted several researchers such as economist Adolph Wagner, historians Georg von Below and Friedrich Meinecke, and jurists Karl von Amira and Paul Lenel.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 1900, Freiburg became the first German university to accept female students.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Before there had been no women at German universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the beginning of the 20th century, several new university buildings were built in the centre of Freiburg, such as the new main building in 1911.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university counted 3,000 students just before World War I.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] After World War I, the philosophers Edmund Husserl and Martin Heidegger (since 1928) taught at Albert Ludwigs University, as well as Edith Stein.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the field of social sciences, Walter Eucken developed the idea of ordoliberalism, which subsequently is known as the "Freiburg School".
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] During the time of the Nazi dictatorship, the university went through the process of "political alignment" (*Gleichschaltung*) like the rest of the German universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Under the rector Martin Heidegger, all Jewish faculty members were forced to leave the university in accordance with the Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] He also informed the Gestapo of the pacifist leanings of a distinguished Faculty member, Hermann Staudinger.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The Nazi geneticist Eugen Fischer promoted racist views while a member of the university, ideas which were used to support the notorious Nuremberg laws passed by the Nazis.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] After World War II, the University of Freiburg was reopened.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] New buildings for natural sciences were erected in the *Institutsviertel* ("institute quarter").
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the postwar years, the ideas of ordoliberalism, developed earlier by economists of the Freiburg School, such as Walter Eucken, Franz Böhm, Hans Grossmann-Doerth, and Leonhard Miksch, drove the creation of the German social market economy and its attendant *Wirtschaftswunder*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Nobel Prize winner and former professor at the University of Freiburg, Friedrich Hayek, is also associated with this theory.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] He directed the Walter Eucken Institut, an economic think tank in Freiburg cooperating with the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Arnold Bergstraesser, considered a founding father or German political science after World War II, was also a professor at the University of Freiburg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] His research group later formed what is now the Arnold Bergstraesser Institute for sociocultural research at the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the late 20th century, the university was part of a mass education campaign and expanded rapidly.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The student body grew to 10,000 by the 1960s, and doubled to 20,000 students by 1980.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the 1970s, the faculty structure was changed to 14 departments, with the Faculty of Engineering becoming the 15th faculty in 1994.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 2002, the number of faculties was reduced to 11.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university opened a memorial dedicated to the victims of National Socialism among the students, staff, and faculty in 2003.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 2006, the University of Freiburg joined the League of European Research Universities (LERU).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] One year later, the university was chosen as one of nine German Universities of Excellence.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] However, it did not receive the third line of funding in 2012.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The seal of the University of Freiburg depicts Christ seated on a gothic throne holding the gospel in his right hand with the temple curtain in the background.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Christ offers the teachings of the gospel to the Jewish scholars who are crouched at his feet.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] To the left and right of Christ are structures resembling towers, most likely symbolic of the Temple of Jerusalem.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Located to the right of Christ is the coat of arms of the Austrian duchies, a banner with five eagles.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The shield on the opposite side symbolizes the coat of arms used by the Habsburgs in conjunction with their territories.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The coat of arms of the city of Freiburg is located at the bottom of the seal, displaying St George's Cross.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The Latin inscription on the seal reads *Sigillum universitatis studii friburgensis brisgaudie*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The seal was slightly modified in 1913, but has otherwise been in continuous use since it was adopted in 1462.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Having grown with the city since the 15th century, the university's buildings are deeply intertwined with the city.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The three large campuses are the university center next to the historical city center, the institutes quarter, and the engineering campus, but other buildings can be found scattered throughout Freiburg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university complex in the historical center of Freiburg contains such picturesque buildings as the Jugendstil *Kollegiengebäude I*(short: "KG I"), built in 1911 by Hermann Billing, and the gothic revival old university library.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The current University Library is also located in the historical center; it is a monumental building erected in the 1970s, and was to be renovated and redesigned beginning in September 2008.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It is one of the largest in Germany and placed fourth in an October 2007, German national ranking of university libraries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University Church, located across from *Kollegiengebäude II* (short: "KG II"), was built in 1683 by the Jesuit order.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The church and the Jesuit college were handed over to the university after the Jesuit order was suppressed in 1773.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The church was destroyed in the 27 November 1944, bombing raid on Freiburg, and reconstructed in 1956.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The "institute quarter" (*Institutsviertel*) is home to the science faculties.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] This campus was destroyed almost completely in the Freiburg bombing raid in 1944.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] After World War II, the reconstruction of the institutes began.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Today, the quarter houses the physics buildings, the tall main chemistry building, visible from afar, the famous Institute for Macromolecular Chemistry at the Hermann-Staudinger-Haus, various other science buildings, and the preclinical institutes of the Faculty of Medicine.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The engineering campus is located next to the small Freiburg airfield to the northwest of the city center, close to the University Medical Center.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The campus is home to the *Institut für Mikrosystemtechnik* ( Department of Microsystems Engineering) and the Department of Computer Science.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] With the addition of the Faculty of Engineering, the University of Freiburg became the first classical university to combine traditional disciplines with microsystems technologies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University Medical Center (*Universitätsklinikum Freiburg*) is one of Germany's largest medical centers.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It boasts 1,600 beds and handles 55,000 in-patients a year, with another 357,000 being treated as out-patients.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It consists of 13 specialized clinics, five clinical institutes, and five centers (e.g.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University Medical Center achieved many technical advances, such as the first implantation of an artificial heart *Jarvik 2000* in 2002.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Most recently, the University of Freiburg purchased a large historic villa in the district of Herdern, which will house part of the literature and linguistics, as well as history departments of the Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 2015, the University of Freiburg opened its new library, housed in a modern building with a large glass and chrome facade.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The library features a section for quiet work and the permanent collection as well as space for group work, where collaboration is encouraged.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The building also includes a student cafe and an outdoor plaza with modern sculpture.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university has a combined undergraduate and graduate student population of around 21,600.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] About 16% of these students are foreigners, from about 120 countries.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Admission largely depends on the faculty and program applied for and is strictly merit based, with the average score of final secondary-school examinations (German *Abitur*) or A-levels playing an important role.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Overall, in the fall of 2010, roughly 4,000 of around 26,000 applicants were admitted: this means that the university's acceptance rate that year was equal to 15.38%.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg offers a large variety of undergraduate, graduate, and postdoctoral degree programs at its 11 faculties in 150 fields of study.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] As common among German universities, the academic year consists of summer and winter terms (semesters).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The winter term runs from 1 October to 31 March, while the summer term runs from 1 April to 30 September.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] However, lectures and classes usually do not run for the full duration of these periods and allow for breaks in spring and fall.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] As a German university, tuition is mostly free.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg currently has a semester fee of 180 EUR for all undergraduate and most graduate and doctoral programs.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Additionally, since autumn 2017, non-EU students are charged 1500 EUR tuition fee per semester.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Numerous student clubs and organizations are active, among them a campus news station, uniCROSS which is a cross-media platform run by students.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It consists of the "uniFM" team, which brings the news as a radio format, the "uniTV" team, producing videos and the "uniONLINE" team which is responsible for the magazine.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Because of the nearby French and Swiss borders and the adjacent Black Forest, where the university owns a retreat on Schauinsland Mountain, fine opportunities exist for leisure and outdoor activities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Students come from Central and Eastern Europe for language studies, the majority demographic category is females in age range 18–25 (58%).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university provides student housing in its various dormitories, run by the *Studentenwerk*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Additionally, further dormitories in Freiburg are operated by other institutions, such as the Catholic Archdiocese.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Due to the affordable rent and limited spots, rooms in the various dormitories are very popular.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Many students find private living arrangements, such as *Wohngemeinschaften* (shared apartments).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] However, the popularity of Freiburg for prospective students can make finding an apartment or room quite time-consuming, especially before the start of the academic terms.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university has its own career center, singled out as one of the best in Germany by the *Stifterverband für die Deutsche Wissenschaft*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university scored well with its submissions to the German Universities Excellence Initiative.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university received funding in all three categories.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] To that end, the university founded the Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies (FRIAS).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Being selected for the third category ranks Freiburg as one of nine "excellence universities" in Germany.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university is to receive over EUR 130 million in additional funds over five years (from 2007) from this third category of funding.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 2009, the university was also successful in a nationwide competition for excellence in teaching, held by the *Stifterverband der deutschen Wissenschaft*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg, with its plans for future innovative teaching concepts, was selected as one of 10 winners from a field of over 100 higher education institutions.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Citing insufficient evidence of integration of the FRIAS concept into the university's framework, the committee did not extend funding for the FRIAS and the institutional strategy line of funding, despite acknowledging the impressive research and advances achieved at FRIAS in the past years.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg is recognized in several university ranking systems.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In the *QS World University Rankings* 2024, it holds the 192nd position globally and the 9th position nationally.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* 2024 placed it 128th in the world and 11th in Germany.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The *Academic Ranking of World Universities* (*ARWU*) 2023 ranks it between 101st and 150th globally, and 5th nationally.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In university rankings published in 2007 and 2008 by German magazines and periodicals (*Der Spiegel, Die Zeit, Focus*, etc.) the University of Freiburg has established itself as one of Germany's top universities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The faculties for law, medicine, economics, history, English studies, German studies, biology, dentistry, and pharmacology achieve especially high scores.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In regards to the natural sciences, the University of Freiburg ranked sixth in Europe and second in Germany in a ranking from 2003 of the European Commission of the universities according to their overall impact on scientific research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The Centre for Higher Education Development, a German higher education think tank, periodically publishes comprehensive rankings of European Master's and PhD programs.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 2016, Freiburg garnered five spots in the top Excellence Group among seven subject fields examined.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In a recent survey by the Nature Publishing Group, the *Nature Publishing Index – 2012 Global Top 100*, the University of Freiburg was the highest-ranked German university and ranked 66th worldwide and 18th in Europe.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] A recent study, "Benchmarking China and Germany: An Analysis of Patent Portfolios of Universities and Research Organizations", was published in May 2013 and sought to evaluate leading universities and research institutions in Germany and China in regards to their patent applications.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The study placed the University of Freiburg as the third-most innovative university in Germany in terms of total patent applications.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Teams of the University of Freiburg frequently participate in academic competitions with considerable success.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The moot court team of the Faculty of Law has been the most successful team in the history of the competition Willem C.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Vis International Commercial Arbitration Moot.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The humanoid robot team of the Faculty of Engineering regularly competes with distinction in international tournaments.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg team has also repeatedly scored highly at the International Genetically Engineered Machine undergraduate synthetic biology competition held at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The team was supported by numerous university institutions, among them the recently established *bioss* cluster of excellence.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg also participates in the National Model United Nations held annually in New York City.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The genetically engineered golden rice was developed by the University of Freiburg (Peter Beyer) and the ETH Zurich (Ingo Potrykus) from 1992 to 2000.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It was considered a breakthrough in biotechnology at the time of publication and now can help to provide vitamin A to people lacking access to it in their diets.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] When previous rector Jäger retired in 2008, law professor Andreas Voßkuhle was chosen as his successor.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] However, shortly after the start of his term, the Social Democratic Party of Germany nominated Voßkuhle as vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Voßkuhle accepted the nomination, was confirmed, and took his seat on the court in May 2008.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In July 2008, then vice-rector Hans-Jochen Schiewer was elected as successor to Voßkuhle.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Schiewer has assumed the position of rector with the start of the winter term 2008/2009.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg offers educational audio and video contents on the iTunes U software platform since January 2008.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg Institute of Physics is actively involved with research at the Large Hadron Collider and has contributed significantly to the ATLAS experiment, resulting in the discovery of the Higgs boson in 2012.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Today, about 430 professors, 3,695 academic employees, and 8,644 non-academic employees at the university are working for the Albert Ludwigs University, making it Freiburg's and the region's biggest employer.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university attracts many academics from abroad and was awarded excellent positions in the 2005 and 2009 *Humboldt Ranking*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] University College Freiburg (UCF) is the university's central facility for promoting and administering international, interdisciplinary teaching activities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It was established in 2012 and is situated in the historical buildings of the old university, the historical site of the *artes liberales*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] UCF serves as a lab for innovative teaching approaches and instructional design at the University of Freiburg and works in close co-operation with the faculties and the Rectorate's departments for Instructional Development and International Relations.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It is accredited by the University of Freiburg, which draws its authority from the Central Evaluation and Accreditation Agency.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The four-year, English-taught Bachelor program in Liberal Arts and Sciences (LAS) is UCF's major offering, the first of its kind in Germany.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] It emphasizes a broad interdisciplinary education, while at the same time providing for individualized academic concentrations on a high academic level.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Students have to complete 240 ECTS credits and are able to major in life sciences, environmental and sustainability sciences, culture and history and governance.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Electives can be taken at UCF, in the greater University of Freiburg, during studies abroad or in the form of internships and self-directed practical projects.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In order to provide a framework and didactic guidance for interdisciplinary higher education, the University of Freiburg has established two chairs at UCF: Epistemology and Theory of Science (Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Frieder Vogelmann, who is also the dean of studies) and Science and Technology Studies (Prof.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The college and the program are directed by Managing Director Paul Sterzel and the Academic Coordinator Thorsten Leiendecker.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Students at UCF organize a number of interest groups, for instance a magazine publishing group, a 3D printing group, an arts collective, and a Model United Nations team.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] They represented by an elected board of twelve student office holders.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Alumni are a part of a subgroup within the greater University of Freiburg alumni association.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg has a variety of graduate education and research opportunities.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In an evaluation of European graduate programs, Freiburg was ranked among the leading universities in several subject fields examined.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] One of the notable graduate opportunities is the Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies, a project funded by the German Excellence Initiative.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Apart from the many graduate programs of its faculties, Freiburg has set up additional specialized graduate schools and graduate research centers, coordinated by the newly founded International Graduate Academy (IGA) Freiburg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg has offered German language courses for foreign students since 1911.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The courses take place at the university's Language Teaching Centre ('Sprachlehrinstitut') during the semester breaks and attract students from over 50 nations..
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The intensive language lessons are bolstered by a supplementary program with lectures and seminars on German culture, politics, philosophy, and art, as well as excursions to the Black Forest, the Alsace region in France, Basel (Switzerland) or Lake Constance.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In addition to classes for all language levels, professional German courses (e.g. business German) are also offered.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The city of Freiburg is known for its environmentally friendly policies and focus on renewable energy and sustainability, attracting solar industry and research to the city.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] This environmentally conscious attitude also extends to the University of Freiburg which has founded the work group "Nachhaltige Universität Freiburg" (Sustainable University of Freiburg) and has drawn up environmental guidelines to be implemented in university practice.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university has also founded the initiative Solar-Uni Freiburg in 2007, with the aim of further expanding its capabilities in sustainability and environmental research.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Solar panels were installed on the roofs of university buildings.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] To bundle renewable energy research and teaching at the university, the Center for Renewable Energy (ZEE, Zentrum für Erneuerbare Energien), an interdisciplinary and cross-faculty facility, was founded.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Aside from research in the fields of solar energy, biomass, geothermal energy, energy efficiency and new energies, an international Master of Science degree in Renewable Energy Management is being offered.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg cooperates closely with external research institutions located in Freiburg, several of which are connected with chairs at the university.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university is part of the regional EUCOR federation together with the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology, the universities of Basel, Mulhouse, and, marked by particularly close ties, Strasbourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Freiburg is further a member of the League of European Research Universities; the European University Association; ASEA-Uninet; AC21; and the International Forum of Public Universities (IFPU).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university also has exchange agreements and cooperative efforts with universities on almost every continent.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The University of Freiburg initiated an English language international master's program in social sciences, the Global Studies Programme (GSP) in 2001.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The aim of the program is to enable students to study social sciences in different regions and cultures.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Combining various disciplines such as sociology, political sciences, anthropology and geography, students approach globalization with a unique perspective.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Students in the GSP master's program study on three different continents during the two-year degree program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Since 2008, the GSP also offers a PhD program in Global Studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The Global Studies Program has received many awards, among them the BMW Group Award for Intercultural Learning in 2004 as well as being listed a Top Ten International master's degree Course in Germany by the German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD) in 2006.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] In 1995, the University of Freiburg helped the Aromanian professor Vasile Barba found the European Center of Aromanian Studies (Aromanian: *Tsentrul European ti Studii Armãneshti*; German: *Europäisches Zentrum für Aromunische Studien*), specialized on Aromanian studies.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] The university also supports the Institute for Russian-German Literature and Cultural Relations at the Russian State University for the Humanities as well as the Vladimir Admoni School for Doctoral Studies at the University of Latvia.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Approximately 1/6th of its students are international students.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Many students at this university participate in the ERASMUS exchange program.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Perhaps best known amongst the alumni of the university are Joseph Goebbels, Martin Heidegger, Edmund Husserl, Hannah Arendt, Paul Ehrlich, Hans Krebs, Hans Spemann, Ethel Dench Puffer Howes, and Friedrich Hayek.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-ludwigs-university-of-freiburg] Among the affiliates are numerous Nobel laureates and Leibniz Prize winners.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-pintat] Pintat graduated from the University of Fribourg in Switzerland in 1967, majoring in economics.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-pintat] He is a member of the Liberal Party of Andorra and was the foreign minister of Andorra from 1997 to 2001.
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-pintat] He also served as Ambassador to the European Union (1995 to 1997) and to Switzerland and the United Kingdom (2001 to 2004).
[src:university-of-fribourg/albert-pintat] He held the position of head of government since being appointed by the General Council on 27 May 2005 until 5 June 2009.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] In the early years of the 20th century, fraternity life in Europe became more and more time-consuming.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Fraternity students had to be present at a large number of festivities such as balls, kneipen, and kommerse.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] This cost time and money which the students would have needed for their studies – idle semesters with no actual study success were common.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The very strict rules and the obligation to consume alcohol in these fraternities made it even more difficult to follow a meaningful daily routine at university and the reputation of the students was very bad.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Because of these reasons, some of the members of the AKV Alemannia – another still existing fraternity in Fribourg – decided in 1918 to separate and found a new fraternity, the AV Fryburgia.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The AV Fryburgia was therewith the second *“reform”* fraternity in Switzerland, following AV Berchtoldia (in Bern) and followed by AV Welfen (in Zurich) and AV Froburger (in Basel).
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The goals of these fraternities were to concentrate more on science, religion, and social responsibility.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Some old fraternity traditions that were seen as superfluous were abandoned, while others were maintained.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The infamous *“trinkzwang”* – forced drinking – was abandoned.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The importance of the fraternity grew and until the 1970s it was one of the big and dominant fraternities in Fribourg and the Swiss Student Society.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] It only suffered – as did all other fraternities in Switzerland – during World War II when large numbers of students were drafted for military service.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Around the war years, some members separated from AV Fryburgia to form new fraternities, the AV Staufer in 1937 and the CA Rezia in 1957.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Unlike the separation from the AKV Alemannia, these fraternities separated on good terms.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] During 1980, the AV Fryburgia became the first and only fraternity in Switzerland to have two members of the Swiss Federal Council at the same time, Kurt Furgler and Hans Hürlimann.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Today the fraternity still occasionally opposes the conservative mainstream inside the SSS.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] AV Fryburgia is part of the so-called *“reform”*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Although it does have certain drinking traditions, there is no mandatory drinking.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The activities of the fraternity shall be limited to a reasonable amount.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The center of fraternity life is the weekly Stammtisch (*“regular’s table”*) which is a mandatory event for the members.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Quick and successful accomplishment of the studies is promoted, as well as sports.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The fraternity bears colors and rejects the tradition of student fencing as being inconsistent with Christian ideas as well as pomposity such as the use of horses on parades (i.e. the Corpus Christi procession).
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The Motto of the fraternity is *Treu, ehrlich und stolz!* or "T.e.u.s.!; *„Loyal, honest and proud!“*.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] It declares the values that should guide the members.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The coat of arms of the fraternity is divided into six parts.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] Behind the colors and the monogram it displays in the upper half the colors of the SSS (red-white-green), the Swiss cross, and the rising sun (last sentence of the fraternities anthem: “Sonne, Sonne, ringe Dich durch!” – *lit. “The sun shall prevail”*).
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] In the lower half, it shows the ancient seal of the University of Fribourg and the coat of arms of the City of Fribourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] The fraternity's anthem was written by famous Swiss composer Abbé Joseph Bovet who also composed "Our chalet", a song of the French Resistance.
[src:university-of-fribourg/av-fryburgia] It is one of the very few student anthems with an own melody.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The **University of Fribourg** (French: *Université de Fribourg*; German: *Universität Freiburg*) is a public university located in Fribourg, Switzerland.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The roots of the university can be traced back to 1580, when the notable Jesuit Peter Canisius founded the Collège Saint-Michel in Fribourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] In 1763, an academy of law was founded by the state of Fribourg which formed the nucleus of the present law faculty.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The University of Fribourg was finally created in 1889 by an Act of the parliament of the Swiss Canton of Fribourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The University of Fribourg is Switzerland's only bilingual university and offers full curricula in both French and German, two of Switzerland's national languages.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Students number about 10,000; there are about 200 tenured professors and 700 other academic teaching and research personnel.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The Misericorde Campus, constructed between 1939 and 1942, was designed by the architects Honegger and Dumas, students of Swiss architect Le Corbusier.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] There are five faculties: Catholic theology, law, natural sciences, humanities, and economics and social sciences.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The university owes its earliest origin to the foundation of the Jesuit College St.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Michel on Belze Hill by Peter Canisius in 1580 at the invitation of the government of Fribourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] In 1763, an Academy of Law was founded, housed in the Albertinium (now a Dominican residence).
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] In 1834, the cantonal library was formed from works brought to Fribourg (from Catholic monasteries) for safekeeping.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Michel was closed following the expulsion of the Jesuits from Fribourg after the canton's defeat in the Sonderbund war.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] In 1886, Georges Python, founder of the cantonal bank and State Counsellor for Fribourg (M.P. in the upper house of the Swiss parliament) became Director of Public Education.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] He raised funds through a lottery and was granted some 2,500,000 CHF by the canton.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The cantonal library became integrated with that of the university and the academy became the Faculty of Law.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] In 1939, the university moved to a new campus constructed on the former cemetery of Misericorde, ceding St.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Michel to one of Fribourg's gymnasia, which took the name College St.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] During the Second World War, the university set up "university camps" along with the University of Zürich, Handels-Hochschule in St.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Gallen and a Lycée camp at Wetzikon provided a wide variety of courses to educate Polish prisoners of war.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The Perolles campus was constructed on the site of a former wagon factory.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Although many lectures were originally in Latin, Fribourg is now the only French/German bilingual university in the world (45% French and 55% German).
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The town itself is 70% French and 30% German.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] This fact, coupled with the traditional dominance of French as the language of the city aristocracy explains why French has remained so dominant in university administration and in the AGEF (Association Générale des Etudiants Fribourgois), the Student's Union.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] To commemorate the centenary of the university, La Poste issued a stamp depicting the figures Science and Sagesse.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] In 2005, the university inaugurated its Perolles 2 campus, to which the Faculty of Economics and Social Science relocated.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The university has the third largest collection of Biblical antiquities in the world after the British Museum and the Cairo Museum.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Fribourg has also developed FriMat, a centre of excellence in nanotechnology.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] As part of the BeNeFri association comprising the Universities of Berne, Neuchâtel and Fribourg, students at any one of these universities may take courses at another in the association and still receive credit at their home institution.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The academic degrees were the Demi-Licence, Licence, DEA / DESS, Doctorate.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The university now follows the requirements of the Bologna process.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The University of Fribourg launched for the 2009–2010 academic year a new postgraduate law programme, the Master of Laws in Cross-Cultural Business Practice (MLCBP), an LL.M taught entirely in English.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] Fribourg has no central campus and its buildings are located throughout the city.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The university seal depicts a cross and bishop's ring representing the university's Catholic ethos on a shield of black and white, representing the canton of Fribourg.
[src:university-of-fribourg/university-of-fribourg] The logo of the university is a blue stylized "F" (with triangles echoing the facade structure of the Miséricorde Building and symbolizing the Alps) and the name of the university in Latin.
